Note:
This file handles auto-vectorization preparation for MIR.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Process loop vectorization analysis and SIMD opportunity detection
- Handle data dependency analysis and vectorization safety checking
- Manage alignment analysis and memory access pattern recognition
- Process vector width selection and cost modeling

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Vectorization enables SIMD instructions for massive performance gains
- Proper vectorization analysis is critical for modern CPU utilization
- Auto-vectorization allows scalar code to benefit from vector hardware

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- Loop vectorization candidate identification
- Data dependency analysis (RAW, WAR, WAW hazards)
- Memory access pattern analysis and alignment checking
- Vector cost modeling and profitability analysis
:End Note

Note: ============================================================================
Note: IMPORTS
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir.runa" as MIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir_nodes.runa" as MIRNodes
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/cfg.runa" as CFG
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/ssa.runa" as SSA
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/dominance.runa" as Dominance
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dictionary
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/set.runa" as Set
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as String

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPE DEFINITIONS - Vectorization Structures
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
VectorizationContext is the main context for the vectorization pass.
It tracks all vectorization analysis results, costs, and transformation state.

Memory Layout (136 bytes):
- cfg: MIRCFG pointer
- ssa_ptr: SSA information pointer
- dominance_ptr: Dominance tree pointer
- loops: List of LoopInfo pointers (vectorizable loops)
- vectorized_loops: Count of successfully vectorized loops
- rejected_loops: Count of loops that failed vectorization
- total_instructions_vectorized: Count of scalar instructions replaced
- vector_width_used: Most common vector width (4, 8, 16)
- loop_candidates: Dictionary mapping loop_id → VectorLoopInfo
- memory_accesses: Dictionary mapping loop_id → List[MemoryAccess]
- dependencies: Dictionary mapping loop_id → DependencyGraph
- cost_models: Dictionary mapping loop_id → CostModel
- alignment_cache: Dictionary mapping value_id → alignment
- runtime_check_inserted: Count of runtime dependency checks inserted
- profitability_threshold: Minimum speedup ratio (default 1.2)
- target_vector_width: Target SIMD width (4 for SSE, 8 for AVX2, 16 for AVX512)
- allow_reductions: Boolean flag for reduction vectorization
@End Reasoning

Type called "VectorizationContext":
    cfg as Integer
    ssa_ptr as Integer
    dominance_ptr as Integer
    loops as Integer
    vectorized_loops as Integer
    rejected_loops as Integer
    total_instructions_vectorized as Integer
    vector_width_used as Integer
    loop_candidates as Integer
    memory_accesses as Integer
    dependencies as Integer
    cost_models as Integer
    alignment_cache as Integer
    runtime_checks_inserted as Integer
    profitability_threshold as Integer
    target_vector_width as Integer
    allow_reductions as Integer
End Type

Note: Size: 17 fields * 8 bytes = 136 bytes

@Reasoning
VectorLoopInfo describes a loop that is a candidate for vectorization.
It stores all properties needed to determine vectorizability and transformation.

Memory Layout (112 bytes):
- loop_header_id: Block ID of loop header
- preheader_id: Block ID of preheader (for inserting vector prologue)
- body_blocks: Set of block IDs in loop body
- exit_blocks: Set of block IDs that exit the loop
- induction_var: SSA value ID of primary induction variable (i)
- trip_count: Compile-time trip count if known, 0 if unknown
- stride: Induction variable stride (usually 1)
- vectorizable: Boolean flag indicating vectorization safety
- rejection_reason: String pointer explaining why not vectorizable (or 0)
- vector_factor: Chosen vectorization factor (2, 4, 8, 16)
- has_reductions: Boolean flag for reduction operations
- reduction_ops: List of reduction operation instruction pointers
- memory_accesses_count: Number of memory operations in loop
- is_innermost: Boolean flag indicating innermost loop
@End Reasoning

Type called "VectorLoopInfo":
    loop_header_id as Integer
    preheader_id as Integer
    body_blocks as Integer
    exit_blocks as Integer
    induction_var as Integer
    trip_count as Integer
    stride as Integer
    vectorizable as Integer
    rejection_reason as Integer
    vector_factor as Integer
    has_reductions as Integer
    reduction_ops as Integer
    memory_accesses_count as Integer
    is_innermost as Integer
End Type

Note: Size: 14 fields * 8 bytes = 112 bytes

@Reasoning
MemoryAccess describes a single load or store operation within a loop.
Critical for stride analysis, alignment checking, and dependency analysis.

Memory Layout (88 bytes):
- instruction_ptr: Pointer to MIR load/store instruction
- base_address: SSA value ID of base pointer
- index_value: SSA value ID of array index (may be induction var)
- stride: Access stride in elements (1 for unit stride, -1 for reverse)
- element_size: Size of accessed element in bytes
- is_load: Boolean flag (1 for load, 0 for store)
- is_store: Boolean flag (1 for store, 0 for load)
- alignment: Known alignment in bytes (1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64)
- is_consecutive: Boolean flag for consecutive access pattern
- is_loop_invariant_address: Boolean flag for invariant base
- depends_on: List of MemoryAccess pointers this depends on
@End Reasoning

Type called "MemoryAccess":
    instruction_ptr as Integer
    base_address as Integer
    index_value as Integer
    stride as Integer
    element_size as Integer
    is_load as Integer
    is_store as Integer
    alignment as Integer
    is_consecutive as Integer
    is_loop_invariant_address as Integer
    depends_on as Integer
End Type

Note: Size: 11 fields * 8 bytes = 88 bytes

@Reasoning
DependencyInfo represents a single data dependency between two memory operations.
Three types of dependencies (RAW, WAR, WAW) affect vectorization safety.

Dependency Types:
- RAW (Read After Write): True dependency, prevents vectorization if loop-carried
- WAR (Write After Read): Anti-dependency, can be resolved with privatization
- WAW (Write After Write): Output dependency, can be resolved with privatization

Memory Layout (72 bytes):
- source_access: MemoryAccess pointer (earlier operation)
- target_access: MemoryAccess pointer (later operation)
- dependency_type: 1=RAW, 2=WAR, 3=WAW
- distance: Loop-carried distance (0=same iteration, >0=loop-carried)
- is_loop_carried: Boolean flag indicating cross-iteration dependency
- can_privatize: Boolean flag indicating if privatization resolves dependency
- can_runtime_check: Boolean flag for runtime disambiguation
- proven_independent: Boolean flag if proven no dependency exists
- analysis_confidence: 0-100 indicating certainty (100=proven)
@End Reasoning

Type called "DependencyInfo":
    source_access as Integer
    target_access as Integer
    dependency_type as Integer
    distance as Integer
    is_loop_carried as Integer
    can_privatize as Integer
    can_runtime_check as Integer
    proven_independent as Integer
    analysis_confidence as Integer
End Type

Note: Size: 9 fields * 8 bytes = 72 bytes

@Reasoning
CostModel estimates the cost and benefit of vectorizing a loop.
Vectorization is only profitable if speedup exceeds profitability threshold.
Memory Layout (88 bytes):
- scalar_cost: Estimated cycles for scalar execution
- vector_cost: Estimated cycles for vectorized execution
- overhead_cost: Prologue/epilogue/alignment overhead
- speedup_ratio: vector_cost / scalar_cost (higher is better)
- is_profitable: Boolean flag indicating profitability
- vector_operations: Count of vectorizable operations
- scalar_operations: Count of non-vectorizable (remain scalar) operations
- memory_operations: Count of memory operations
- reduction_cost: Extra cost for horizontal reductions
- gather_scatter_cost: Extra cost for non-consecutive access
- estimated_trip_count: Runtime trip count estimate for profitability
@End Reasoning

Type called "CostModel":
    scalar_cost as Integer
    vector_cost as Integer
    overhead_cost as Integer
    speedup_ratio as Integer
    is_profitable as Integer
    vector_operations as Integer
    scalar_operations as Integer
    memory_operations as Integer
    reduction_cost as Integer
    gather_scatter_cost as Integer
    estimated_trip_count as Integer
End Type

Note: Size: 11 fields * 8 bytes = 88 bytes

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONTEXT MANAGEMENT
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_vectorization_context" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocates and initializes the per-function VectorizationContext that holds
    every shared analysis result for the duration of the pass. The context
    owns:
    - The CFG and SSA pointers (borrowed; not freed on destroy)
    - The dominance tree (computed here, freed on destroy)
    - The per-loop info list, candidates dictionary, memory_accesses
      dictionary, dependencies dictionary, and cost_models dictionary -
      all owned, all freed by destroy_vectorization_context
    - Counters and configuration knobs (vector width, profitability threshold)

    DEFAULT CONFIGURATION:
    - target_vector_width = 4 (SSE baseline; ABI-portable on all x86_64
      cores from Pentium 4 onward). AVX2 cores can be bumped to 8 and
      AVX-512 cores to 16 by the target-selection driver.
    - profitability_threshold = 1.2x (stored fixed-point as 120). Below
      this speedup ratio the vectorizer rejects the loop because the
      runtime guard overhead would erase any small gain.
    - allow_reductions = 1 (enable vectorization of accumulator patterns
      via horizontal-reduce epilogues).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The context is a flat 136-byte structure of Integer (i.e. pointer-sized)
    fields. Pointers to owned sub-structures are stored at fixed offsets so
    the destroy routine can locate them deterministically. Dominance tree
    computation is the dominant cost of context creation; it is performed
    eagerly here because every subsequent analysis depends on it.
    @End Implementation

    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Display "create_vectorization_context: null CFG"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Allocate context (136 bytes)
    Let context_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with 136
    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Display "create_vectorization_context: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set CFG
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0, cfg_ptr

    Note: Get SSA information
    Let ssa_ptr be proc get_ssa_info from SSA with cfg_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 8, ssa_ptr

    Note: Compute dominance information
    Display "create_vectorization_context: computing dominance tree"
    Let dom_info be proc compute_dominance_tree from Dominance with cfg_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 16, dom_info

    Note: Create loops list
    Let loops_list be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 24, loops_list

    Note: Initialize counters
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 32, 0 Note: vectorized_loops
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 40, 0 Note: rejected_loops
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 48, 0 Note: total_instructions_vectorized
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 56, 4 Note: vector_width_used (default 4)

    Note: Create dictionaries
    Let loop_candidates be proc create from Dictionary
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 64, loop_candidates

    Let memory_accesses be proc create from Dictionary
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72, memory_accesses

    Let dependencies be proc create from Dictionary
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 80, dependencies

    Let cost_models be proc create from Dictionary
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 88, cost_models

    Let alignment_cache be proc create from Dictionary
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 96, alignment_cache

    Note: Initialize runtime checks counter
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 104, 0

    Note: Set profitability threshold to 1.2 (20% speedup minimum)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 112, 120 Note: Stored as 120 = 1.2 multiplied by 100

    Note: Set target vector width to 4 (SSE baseline, can be increased to 8 for AVX2)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 120, 4

    Note: Allow reductions by default
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 128, 1

    Display "create_vectorization_context: context created successfully"
    Return context_ptr
End Process

Process called "destroy_vectorization_context" that takes context_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Releases every allocation owned by the VectorizationContext. Borrowed
    pointers (CFG, SSA) are left alone; everything created by
    create_vectorization_context or any analysis routine is freed here.

    DEALLOCATION ORDER (must match owning-pointer topology):
    1. loops_list (owns its element VectorLoopInfo pointers, which themselves
       own body_blocks/exit_blocks/reduction_ops/rejection_reason).
    2. loop_candidates dictionary (parallel iteration: each entry has the
       same sub-structures as loops_list entries; both indices into the
       same VectorLoopInfo allocations - the implementation walks both to
       guarantee no double-free).
    3. memory_accesses dictionary (each loop's value is a List of
       MemoryAccess; each MemoryAccess owns a depends_on list).
    4. dependencies dictionary (each loop's value is a List of
       DependencyInfo).
    5. cost_models dictionary (each loop's value is a single CostModel
       allocation).
    6. alignment_cache dictionary (values are scalar alignment integers, no
       sub-allocations).
    7. Dominance tree (owned by Dominance module; freed via its destructor).
    8. The context struct itself.

    Skipping any step would leak; freeing in the wrong order (e.g. context
    before sub-structures) would dangle the iteration pointers used to walk
    the dictionaries.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Defensive null checks at every step: each owning pointer is tested
    against 0 before traversal so that a partially-initialized context
    (e.g., from an early-failure path in create_vectorization_context) can
    be safely destroyed without invoking destroy on a null pointer.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope
    Double-free vulnerability avoidance: every allocation is freed exactly
    once, and the dictionaries / lists are torn down before the context
    itself so no field can be read after the underlying allocation is
    released. Use-after-free during teardown is prevented by the strict
    bottom-up order.
    @End Security_Scope

    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Free loops list
    Let loops_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 24
    If loops_list is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from List with loops_list
    End If

    Note: Free loop_candidates dictionary and VectorLoopInfo structures
    Let loop_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 64
    If loop_candidates is not equal to 0:
        Let keys be proc keys from Dictionary with loop_candidates
        Let key_count be proc length from List with keys
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than key_count:
            Let key be proc get from List with keys, i
            Let loop_info be proc get from Dictionary with loop_candidates, key
            If loop_info is not equal to 0:
                Note: Free body_blocks set
                Let body_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16
                If body_blocks is not equal to 0:
                    proc destroy from Set with body_blocks
                End If

                Note: Free exit_blocks set
                Let exit_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 24
                If exit_blocks is not equal to 0:
                    proc destroy from Set with exit_blocks
                End If

                Note: Free reduction_ops list
                Let reduction_ops be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 88
                If reduction_ops is not equal to 0:
                    proc destroy from List with reduction_ops
                End If

                Note: Free rejection_reason string if present
                Let rejection_reason be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 64
                If rejection_reason is not equal to 0:
                    proc deallocate from Layout with rejection_reason
                End If

                Note: Free VectorLoopInfo structure
                proc deallocate from Layout with loop_info
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc destroy from List with keys
        proc destroy from Dictionary with loop_candidates
    End If

    Note: Free memory_accesses dictionary and lists
    Let memory_accesses be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72
    If memory_accesses is not equal to 0:
        Set keys to proc keys from Dictionary with memory_accesses
        Set key_count to proc length from List with keys
        Set i to 0
        While i is less than key_count:
            Set key to proc get from List with keys, i
            Let access_list be proc get from Dictionary with memory_accesses, key
            If access_list is not equal to 0:
                Note: Free each MemoryAccess structure
                Let access_count be proc length from List with access_list
                Let j be 0
                While j is less than access_count:
                    Let mem_access be proc get from List with access_list, j
                    If mem_access is not equal to 0:
                        Note: Free depends_on list
                        Let depends_on be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mem_access, 80
                        If depends_on is not equal to 0:
                            proc destroy from List with depends_on
                        End If
                        proc deallocate from Layout with mem_access
                    End If
                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While
                proc destroy from List with access_list
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc destroy from List with keys
        proc destroy from Dictionary with memory_accesses
    End If

    Note: Free dependencies dictionary and lists
    Let dependencies be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 80
    If dependencies is not equal to 0:
        Set keys to proc keys from Dictionary with dependencies
        Set key_count to proc length from List with keys
        Set i to 0
        While i is less than key_count:
            Set key to proc get from List with keys, i
            Let dep_list be proc get from Dictionary with dependencies, key
            If dep_list is not equal to 0:
                Note: Free each DependencyInfo structure
                Let dep_count be proc length from List with dep_list
                Set j to 0
                While j is less than dep_count:
                    Let dep_info be proc get from List with dep_list, j
                    If dep_info is not equal to 0:
                        proc deallocate from Layout with dep_info
                    End If
                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While
                proc destroy from List with dep_list
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc destroy from List with keys
        proc destroy from Dictionary with dependencies
    End If

    Note: Free cost_models dictionary
    Let cost_models be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 88
    If cost_models is not equal to 0:
        Set keys to proc keys from Dictionary with cost_models
        Set key_count to proc length from List with keys
        Set i to 0
        While i is less than key_count:
            Set key to proc get from List with keys, i
            Let cost_model be proc get from Dictionary with cost_models, key
            If cost_model is not equal to 0:
                proc deallocate from Layout with cost_model
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc destroy from List with keys
        proc destroy from Dictionary with cost_models
    End If

    Note: Free alignment_cache dictionary
    Let alignment_cache be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 96
    If alignment_cache is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Dictionary with alignment_cache
    End If

    Note: Free dominance tree
    Let dom_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 16
    If dom_info is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy_dominance_tree from Dominance with dom_info
    End If

    Note: Free context
    proc deallocate from Layout with context_ptr

    Display "destroy_vectorization_context: context destroyed"
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "print_vectorization_stats" that takes context_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Prints vectorization statistics for debugging and optimization reporting.
    @End Reasoning

    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Display "========== Vectorization Statistics =========="

    Let vectorized_loops be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 32
    Display "Loops vectorized: "
    Display vectorized_loops

    Let rejected_loops be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 40
    Display "Loops rejected: "
    Display rejected_loops

    Let total_instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 48
    Display "Instructions vectorized: "
    Display total_instructions

    Let vector_width be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 56
    Display "Vector width used: "
    Display vector_width

    Let runtime_checks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 104
    Display "Runtime checks inserted: "
    Display runtime_checks

    Display "=============================================="

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LOOP ANALYSIS - Natural Loop Detection and Induction Variable Analysis
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "detect_natural_loops" that takes context_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Identifies the set of natural loops in the function's control flow graph
    using the classical back-edge / dominator algorithm (Dragon Book section
    9.6.4 / Aho-Sethi-Ullman). A natural loop in a CFG is the set of nodes
    that form a strongly-connected region around a single entry point (the
    header) reached via at least one back edge.

    DEFINITIONS:
    - Back edge: an edge B -> H in the CFG such that H dominates B. Domination
      means every path from the function entry to B passes through H, so any
      cycle containing the edge B -> H must re-enter the cycle through H.
    - Loop header: the target H of a back edge. By construction H is the
      single-entry node of the loop.
    - Loop body: the set of CFG nodes that can reach B without passing through
      H; this is computed by reverse-reachability from B in the
      header-removed CFG.

    Only natural loops are candidates for vectorization. Irreducible loops
    (loops with multiple entry points, e.g. produced by goto-based code paths
    in legacy languages) are intentionally skipped by this analyzer because
    they cannot be safely cloned into the vector-prologue / scalar-epilogue
    shape without first canonicalizing them via loop simplification.

    WHY THIS COMES FIRST:
    Every subsequent analysis - induction variables, memory access patterns,
    dependency checking - is parameterized by a single loop. Detect_natural_
    loops produces the work list for the per-loop pipeline. A function with
    no loops does no further work in this pass and is rejected immediately.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The implementation walks every block and every successor edge, testing
    each edge for the back-edge property via the precomputed dominance tree.
    Each back edge spawns one loop-info record via
    create_loop_info_from_back_edge. Multiple back edges with the same target
    are recognized as one loop with multiple latches; in this implementation
    they currently produce separate VectorLoopInfo records, which is a
    documented limitation - multi-latch loops will be merged in a future
    canonicalization step before this pass.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(B * S) where B is the number of blocks and S is the average successor
    count, plus O(B * H) for the dominance probes where H is the dominator
    tree height (typically O(log B) with a balanced dominator tree).
    @End Performance_Hints

    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let dom_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 16
    Let loops_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 24

    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0 or dom_info is equal to 0 or loops_list is equal to 0:
        Display "detect_natural_loops: invalid context"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get all blocks in CFG
    Let blocks be proc get_all_blocks from CFG with cfg_ptr
    If blocks is equal to 0:
        Display "detect_natural_loops: no blocks in CFG"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let block_count be proc length from List with blocks
    Let loops_found be 0

    Note: For each block, check its successors for back edges
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than block_count:
        Let block_id be proc get from List with blocks, i
        Let successors be proc get_block_successors from CFG with cfg_ptr, block_id

        If successors is not equal to 0:
            Let succ_count be proc length from List with successors
            Let j be 0

            While j is less than succ_count:
                Let succ_id be proc get from List with successors, j

                Note: Check if successor dominates current block (back edge)
                Let is_back_edge be proc dominates from Dominance with dom_info, succ_id, block_id

                If is_back_edge is equal to 1:
                    Display "detect_natural_loops: back edge found: "
                    Display block_id
                    Display " → "
                    Display succ_id

                    Note: Create loop info for this back edge
                    Let loop_info be proc create_loop_info_from_back_edge with context_ptr, block_id, succ_id

                    If loop_info is not equal to 0:
                        proc list_append from ListCore with loops_list, loop_info
                        Set loops_found to loops_found plus 1
                    End If
                End If

                Set j to j plus 1
            End While

            proc destroy from List with successors
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc destroy from List with blocks

    Display "detect_natural_loops: found "
    Display loops_found
    Display " natural loops"

    Return loops_found
End Process

Process called "create_loop_info_from_back_edge" that takes context_ptr as Integer, back_edge_source as Integer, header_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constructs a fresh VectorLoopInfo from a confirmed back edge (latch ->
    header). The record captures the loop's topological skeleton (header,
    preheader, body, exits) but defers IV analysis, memory-access analysis,
    and cost modeling to subsequent per-phase routines.

    POPULATED HERE:
    - loop_header_id, preheader (found-or-created by canonicalization)
    - body_blocks (computed by reverse reachability from the latch)
    - exit_blocks (computed by successor enumeration over body_blocks)
    - default initial values for fields populated later (induction_var=0,
      trip_count=0, stride=1, vectorizable=0, vector_factor=4,
      is_innermost=1)

    The preheader-find-or-create step canonicalizes the loop shape: a
    natural loop without a unique preheader gets one synthesized here, so
    every downstream analysis can assume preheader != 0 and use it as the
    insertion point for vector prologue code.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The default vector_factor of 4 matches the SSE / NEON baseline. The
    target-selection driver may override this via the context's
    target_vector_width after construction. The default is_innermost=1 is
    optimistic; nested-loop detection later in the pipeline may clear it
    for outer loops.
    @End Implementation

    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let dom_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 16

    Note: Allocate VectorLoopInfo (112 bytes)
    Let loop_info be proc allocate from Layout with 112
    If loop_info is equal to 0:
        Display "create_loop_info_from_back_edge: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set header
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 0, header_id

    Note: Find or create preheader
    Let preheader be proc find_or_create_preheader with cfg_ptr, dom_info, header_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 8, preheader

    Note: Compute loop body blocks (blocks that can reach back_edge_source without leaving through header)
    Let body_blocks be proc compute_loop_body with cfg_ptr, dom_info, header_id, back_edge_source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16, body_blocks

    Note: Compute exit blocks (blocks outside loop with predecessors in loop)
    Let exit_blocks be proc compute_exit_blocks with cfg_ptr, body_blocks
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 24, exit_blocks

    Note: Initialize remaining fields
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 32, 0 Note: induction_var (unknown)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 40, 0 Note: trip_count (unknown)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 48, 1 Note: stride (assume 1)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 56, 0 Note: vectorizable (not yet analyzed)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 64, 0 Note: rejection_reason (none)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 72, 4 Note: vector_factor (default 4)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 80, 0 Note: has_reductions (not yet analyzed)

    Let reduction_ops be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 88, reduction_ops

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 96, 0 Note: memory_accesses_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 104, 1 Note: is_innermost (assume yes)

    Return loop_info
End Process

Process called "compute_loop_body" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer, dom_info as Integer, header_id as Integer, back_edge_source as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes the set of CFG blocks that constitute a natural loop's body
    using the standard reverse-reachability algorithm from the Dragon Book
    (algorithm 9.46):

      body = { N | N is reachable from back_edge_source in the reverse CFG,
                   not crossing header H }

    Equivalently: starting from the latch, walk predecessor edges, adding
    each visited block to the body. Stop the traversal when we would leave
    the dominance subtree of the header (such a block must lie outside the
    loop because every loop body block is dominated by the header by
    definition).

    The worklist algorithm guarantees termination because the CFG is finite
    and the body Set deduplicates revisits.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Worklist-based BFS. Each pop yields a block; if already in body skip,
    otherwise add to body and enqueue all predecessors that are dominated
    by the header. The dominance test is the loop-exit guard.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(B_loop + E_loop) where B_loop and E_loop are the blocks and edges in
    the loop body. The dominance probe is O(1) amortized with a precomputed
    dominator tree (which the caller already has in dom_info).
    @End Performance_Hints

    Let body_set be proc create from Set
    If body_set is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Header is always in loop body
    proc set_add from Set with body_set, header_id

    Note: Worklist algorithm starting from back_edge_source
    Let worklist be proc create from List
    proc list_append from ListCore with worklist, back_edge_source

    While proc length from List with worklist is greater than 0:
        Note: Pop from worklist
        Let current_id be proc get from List with worklist, 0
        proc list_remove_at from ListCore with worklist, 0

        Note: Add to body if not already present
        Let already_in_body be proc contains from Set with body_set, current_id
        If already_in_body is equal to 0:
            proc set_add from Set with body_set, current_id

            Note: Add predecessors to worklist if dominated by header
            Let predecessors be proc get_block_predecessors from CFG with cfg_ptr, current_id
            If predecessors is not equal to 0:
                Let pred_count be proc length from List with predecessors
                Let i be 0
                While i is less than pred_count:
                    Let pred_id be proc get from List with predecessors, i

                    Note: Only add if dominated by header (inside loop)
                    Let is_dominated be proc dominates from Dominance with dom_info, header_id, pred_id
                    If is_dominated is equal to 1:
                        proc list_append from ListCore with worklist, pred_id
                    End If

                    Set i to i plus 1
                End While
                proc destroy from List with predecessors
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc destroy from List with worklist
    Return body_set
End Process

Process called "compute_exit_blocks" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer, body_blocks as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Identifies every successor of a loop body block that lies outside the
    body itself. These exit targets are the destinations of the loop's
    natural exit edges and must be tracked so that update_loop_structure
    can route them through the scalar epilogue.

    A single loop may have multiple exit blocks (e.g., a normal-fall-through
    exit plus an early-break exit), in which case all exits are merged
    through the epilogue to give exit-phi-nodes a unified producer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    O(B_loop * S) where S is the average successor count. Each successor
    is membership-tested against the body Set; misses are added to the
    exit Set, which de-duplicates multiple body blocks branching to the
    same exit.
    @End Implementation

    Let exit_set be proc create from Set
    If exit_set is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: For each block in loop body, check its successors
    Let body_list be proc to_list from Set with body_blocks
    Let body_count be proc length from List with body_list
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than body_count:
        Let block_id be proc get from List with body_list, i
        Let successors be proc get_block_successors from CFG with cfg_ptr, block_id

        If successors is not equal to 0:
            Let succ_count be proc length from List with successors
            Let j be 0

            While j is less than succ_count:
                Let succ_id be proc get from List with successors, j

                Note: If successor is not in loop body, it's an exit block
                Let in_body be proc contains from Set with body_blocks, succ_id
                If in_body is equal to 0:
                    proc set_add from Set with exit_set, succ_id
                End If

                Set j to j plus 1
            End While

            proc destroy from List with successors
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc destroy from List with body_list
    Return exit_set
End Process

Process called "find_or_create_preheader" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer, dom_info as Integer, header_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the loop's preheader block, creating one if the natural-loop
    shape did not already provide a unique one. The preheader is the canonical
    insertion point for vector-prologue code (alignment peels, trip-count
    guards, runtime alias checks) and for loop-invariant code hoisted by LICM.

    PREHEADER PROPERTIES:
    A preheader for header H is a block P satisfying:
    1. P's only successor is H (so falling off P unconditionally enters
       the loop).
    2. Every predecessor of H that is NOT a loop latch (back-edge source)
       feeds into P instead of directly into H.

    A loop with a unique non-back-edge predecessor of the header already
    has its preheader for free (the most common case after standard CFG
    construction). A loop with multiple non-back-edge predecessors needs
    a synthetic preheader: a fresh empty block is inserted, all
    non-back-edge predecessors are rewired to it, and a single edge from
    the preheader to the header is added. Phi-nodes in the header are
    repaired so that the multiple original predecessor entries collapse
    into a single preheader entry.

    Loop canonicalization to ensure a unique preheader is a precondition
    for the rest of the vectorizer's analysis - downstream passes assume
    they can read the loop's preheader_id field and find a single,
    unambiguous insertion point.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Fast-path detection: when the header has exactly two predecessors (the
    common case of one latch and one preheader), inspect each predecessor's
    successor count - the one with successor count exactly 1 is the
    preheader. If neither matches, fall through to synthetic-preheader
    creation.
    @End Implementation

    Note: Get header predecessors
    Let predecessors be proc get_block_predecessors from CFG with cfg_ptr, header_id
    If predecessors is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pred_count be proc length from List with predecessors

    Note: Check if there's already a unique preheader (single non-back-edge predecessor)
    If pred_count is equal to 2:
        Note: Common case: one back edge + one preheader
        Let pred0 be proc get from List with predecessors, 0
        Let pred1 be proc get from List with predecessors, 1

        Note: Check which one has only header as successor
        Let pred0_succs be proc get_block_successors from CFG with cfg_ptr, pred0
        If pred0_succs is not equal to 0:
            Let pred0_succ_count be proc length from List with pred0_succs
            proc destroy from List with pred0_succs

            If pred0_succ_count is equal to 1:
                proc destroy from List with predecessors
                Return pred0
            End If
        End If

        Let pred1_succs be proc get_block_successors from CFG with cfg_ptr, pred1
        If pred1_succs is not equal to 0:
            Let pred1_succ_count be proc length from List with pred1_succs
            proc destroy from List with pred1_succs

            If pred1_succ_count is equal to 1:
                proc destroy from List with predecessors
                Return pred1
            End If
        End If
    End If

    proc destroy from List with predecessors

    Note: No preheader found, create one now
    Display "find_or_create_preheader: creating new preheader for loop header "
    Display header_id

    Note: Allocate new block ID for preheader
    Let preheader_id be proc allocate_block_id from CFG with cfg_ptr

    Note: Create new basic block
    Let preheader_block be proc create_mir_basic_block from MIR with preheader_id, 0
    If preheader_block is equal to 0:
        Display "find_or_create_preheader: failed to create preheader block"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Add preheader block to CFG
    proc add_block_to_function from CFG with cfg_ptr, preheader_block

    Note: Get header predecessors again to rewire edges
    Let header_preds be proc get_block_predecessors from CFG with cfg_ptr, header_id
    If header_preds is not equal to 0:
        Set pred_count to proc length from List with header_preds
        Let i be 0

        Note: Redirect all non-back-edge predecessors to preheader
        While i is less than pred_count:
            Let pred_id be proc get from List with header_preds, i

            Note: Check if this is a back edge (predecessor is dominated by header)
            Let is_back_edge be proc dominates from Dominance with dom_info, header_id, pred_id

            Note: Only redirect non-back-edge predecessors
            If is_back_edge is equal to 0:
                Note: Redirect this predecessor's successor from header to preheader
                proc redirect_edge from CFG with cfg_ptr, pred_id, header_id, preheader_id
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        proc destroy from List with header_preds
    End If

    Note: Add edge from preheader to header
    proc add_edge from CFG with cfg_ptr, preheader_id, header_id

    Note: Update phi nodes in header to use preheader instead of old predecessors
    Let header_block be proc get_block from CFG with cfg_ptr, header_id
    If header_block is not equal to 0:
        Let phi_nodes be proc get_block_phi_nodes from CFG with header_block
        If phi_nodes is not equal to 0:
            Let phi_count be proc length from List with phi_nodes
            Set i to 0

            While i is less than phi_count:
                Let phi_ptr be proc get from List with phi_nodes, i
                Note: Update phi incoming blocks for non-back-edge values to use preheader
                proc update_phi_predecessors from SSA with phi_ptr, preheader_id
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While

            proc destroy from List with phi_nodes
        End If
    End If

    Display "find_or_create_preheader: created preheader block "
    Display preheader_id

    Return preheader_id
End Process

Process called "analyze_induction_variables" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Locates the primary induction variable (IV) of a candidate loop. A loop is
    not vectorizable without a recognizable IV because every memory address
    in the body must be expressible as base + IV * element_size, and every
    iteration count must be derivable from IV's range.

    INDUCTION VARIABLE DEFINITION (Aho-Sethi-Ullman / Dragon Book classic):
    A SSA value v is a basic induction variable of loop L iff:
      1. v is defined by a phi-node in the loop header
      2. exactly one incoming arc to that phi comes from outside L (initial
         value), and exactly one comes from a loop-latch predecessor (update)
      3. the update value is computed as v + c for some loop-invariant c (the
         stride). c is required to be a compile-time integer constant for the
         vectorizer (variable strides require strided/gather code and a
         runtime trip-count expression; future work).

    Derived induction variables (e.g., j = 2*i + 5 inside the body) are NOT
    enumerated here - they are recognized lazily by compute_access_stride
    during memory-access analysis, which is sufficient for the vectorizer
    because only the address computation needs to be classified.

    WHY UNIT STRIDE MATTERS:
    Stride == 1 is the prerequisite for the consecutive-lane interpretation of
    vector loads/stores. Stride == -1 (reverse iteration) is vectorizable with
    an extra shuffle. Stride > 1 or stride < -1 produces strided/gather
    access. The IV stride therefore propagates into every memory-access
    record produced by the memory-access analyzer downstream.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Walks the header block's phi node list and tests each via
    is_induction_variable. The first matching phi is recorded as the primary
    IV; subsequent matches are ignored because the vectorizer currently
    supports only single-IV loops. Multi-IV vectorization (e.g., affine nested
    loops with row and column induction) is a future extension that requires
    a tuple-IV cost model.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(P) where P is the number of phi nodes in the loop header (typically 1-3
    in practice). The cost of is_induction_variable itself is O(1) per call.
    @End Performance_Hints

    If context_ptr is equal to 0 or loop_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let header_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 0

    Note: Get phi nodes in header block
    Let header_block be proc get_block from CFG with cfg_ptr, header_id
    If header_block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let phi_nodes be proc get_block_phi_nodes from CFG with header_block
    If phi_nodes is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let phi_count be proc length from List with phi_nodes
    Let i be 0
    Let induction_found be 0

    While i is less than phi_count:
        Let phi_ptr be proc get from List with phi_nodes, i

        Note: Check if this phi is an induction variable
        Let is_induction be proc is_induction_variable with context_ptr, loop_info, phi_ptr

        If is_induction is equal to 1:
            Note: Found induction variable, extract stride
            Let phi_result be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi_ptr, 8
            Let stride be proc extract_induction_stride with context_ptr, loop_info, phi_ptr

            Note: Store induction variable and stride in loop info
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 32, phi_result
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 48, stride

            Set induction_found to 1
            Display "analyze_induction_variables: found induction var "
            Display phi_result
            Display " with stride "
            Display stride
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc destroy from List with phi_nodes

    Return induction_found
End Process

Process called "is_induction_variable" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer, phi_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Tests whether a header phi-node has the canonical basic-induction-variable
    shape:

        phi = [ init_value, preheader_block ],
              [ phi + constant_stride, latch_block ]

    Exactly two incoming arcs are required (one from outside the loop carrying
    the initial value, one from the latch carrying the per-iteration update).
    More-arc phis arise from multi-latch or merged-control-flow loops and are
    not yet supported by this vectorizer; they would require canonicalization
    to a single-latch form before this pass.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Classifies each incoming pair by whether its source block is inside the
    loop body. The outside block carries the init value; the inside block
    carries the update. Returns the result of is_induction_update on the
    update value to verify that it has the phi + constant_stride shape.
    @End Implementation

    If phi_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get incoming pairs
    Let incoming_pairs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi_ptr, 16
    Let incoming_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi_ptr, 24

    If incoming_count is not equal to 2:
        Note: Induction variables have exactly 2 incoming values
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get phi result value
    Let phi_result be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi_ptr, 8

    Note: Check both incoming values
    Let value0 be proc get from List with incoming_pairs, 0
    Let block0 be proc get from List with incoming_pairs, 1
    Let value1 be proc get from List with incoming_pairs, 2
    Let block1 be proc get from List with incoming_pairs, 3

    Note: One incoming must be from outside loop (initial value)
    Let body_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16
    Let block0_in_loop be proc contains from Set with body_blocks, block0
    Let block1_in_loop be proc contains from Set with body_blocks, block1

    If block0_in_loop is equal to 1 and block1_in_loop is equal to 0:
        Note: block0 is latch, block1 is preheader
        Note: value0 should be phi + stride
        Let is_update be proc is_induction_update with context_ptr, value0, phi_result
        Return is_update
    End If

    If block1_in_loop is equal to 1 and block0_in_loop is equal to 0:
        Note: block1 is latch, block0 is preheader
        Note: value1 should be phi + stride
        Set is_update to proc is_induction_update with context_ptr, value1, phi_result
        Return is_update
    End If

    Note: Neither pattern matched
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_induction_update" that takes context_ptr as Integer, value_id as Integer, phi_result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Verifies that an SSA value is computed by an MIR_ADD whose operands are
    the phi result (the induction variable's current iteration value) and an
    SSA-level constant (the stride). This is the bottom half of the
    basic-induction-variable check; without a constant stride the loop's
    trip count cannot be expressed as an affine function of iteration index
    and the vectorizer cannot statically tile by VF.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Examines the defining instruction's opcode (must be MIR_ADD == 20100)
    and both operand SSA values; one operand must equal phi_result, the
    other must be an SSA-level integer constant.
    @End Implementation

    Let ssa_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 8
    If ssa_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get defining instruction for value_id
    Let def_inst be proc get_defining_instruction from SSA with ssa_ptr, value_id
    If def_inst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if it's an ADD instruction
    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with def_inst
    If opcode is not equal to 20100:  Note: MIR_ADD = 20100
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if operands are phi_result and a constant
    Let left_operand be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 16
    Let right_operand be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 24

    If left_operand is equal to phi_result:
        Note: Check if right operand is constant
        Let is_const be proc is_constant from SSA with ssa_ptr, right_operand
        Return is_const
    End If

    If right_operand is equal to phi_result:
        Note: Check if left operand is constant
        Set is_const to proc is_constant from SSA with ssa_ptr, left_operand
        Return is_const
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "extract_induction_stride" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer, phi_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Pulls the constant stride out of a recognized basic induction variable's
    update expression. is_induction_variable already proved that the update
    operand is a constant; this routine reads its constant value.

    A stride of 1 corresponds to a normal forward counter (the overwhelmingly
    common case). -1 corresponds to a reverse counter (down to zero, well-
    handled). Strides with |s| > 1 step through the iteration space at a
    non-unit rate; the vectorizer can still widen them but the access
    classifier downstream may force a gather/scatter implementation rather
    than a contiguous VLOAD.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Locates the update value (the one whose source block is inside the loop
    body), follows the SSA def chain to its MIR_ADD, and reads the constant
    operand's value via SSA.get_constant_value. Returns 1 as the safe default
    if any step fails - this default is safe because callers verify
    induction-variable shape before invoking this routine.
    @End Implementation

    Let incoming_pairs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi_ptr, 16
    Let phi_result be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with phi_ptr, 8

    Let value0 be proc get from List with incoming_pairs, 0
    Let value1 be proc get from List with incoming_pairs, 2

    Let body_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16
    Let block0 be proc get from List with incoming_pairs, 1
    Let block1 be proc get from List with incoming_pairs, 3

    Let block0_in_loop be proc contains from Set with body_blocks, block0
    Let block1_in_loop be proc contains from Set with body_blocks, block1

    Let update_value be 0
    If block0_in_loop is equal to 1:
        Set update_value to value0
    End If
    If block1_in_loop is equal to 1:
        Set update_value to value1
    End If

    If update_value is equal to 0:
        Return 1  Note: Default stride
    End If

    Note: Get defining instruction for update value
    Let ssa_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 8
    Let def_inst be proc get_defining_instruction from SSA with ssa_ptr, update_value
    If def_inst is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Extract constant stride from ADD instruction
    Let left_operand be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 16
    Let right_operand be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 24

    If left_operand is equal to phi_result:
        Note: Stride is right operand
        Let stride_value be proc get_constant_value from SSA with ssa_ptr, right_operand
        Return stride_value
    End If

    If right_operand is equal to phi_result:
        Note: Stride is left operand
        Set stride_value to proc get_constant_value from SSA with ssa_ptr, left_operand
        Return stride_value
    End If

    Return 1  Note: Default stride
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DATA DEPENDENCY ANALYSIS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "analyze_loop_dependencies" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Builds the loop-carried data-dependency graph that determines vectorization
    legality. A loop is safe to vectorize if and only if no dependency
    constraint forces a serial ordering of iterations that contradicts the
    parallel-lane execution model.

    DEPENDENCY TAXONOMY:
    For two memory accesses A_i (executed in iteration i) and A_j (executed
    in iteration j > i) to the same memory location:
    - RAW (Read-After-Write, "true" / "flow"): write in iter i, read in iter j.
      Cannot be reordered. If loop-carried (j > i with i and j in same VF
      block), it prevents vectorization unless the distance is exactly 0
      (same iteration, easily handled by lane ordering) or >= VF (cross-VF,
      handled by the natural lane sequencing). Distance 1 to VF-1 is fatal.
    - WAR (Write-After-Read, "anti"): read in iter i, write in iter j. Can be
      resolved by SSA renaming / scalar privatization: rename the write to a
      fresh value and the read continues to see the old value.
    - WAW (Write-After-Write, "output"): write in iter i, write in iter j.
      Resolvable by privatization (only the last write matters; in the vector
      lane interpretation each lane's write is the "last" for its lane).
    - RAR (Read-After-Read): not a dependency; both reads can occur in any
      order. The pair-checking loop here explicitly skips RAR pairs.

    DISTANCE / DIRECTION VECTOR:
    The dependency distance vector measures how many iterations separate A_i
    from A_j. Distance 0 means same-iteration (safe under vectorization);
    distance >= VF means cross-VF (safe); distance 1..VF-1 means
    within-VF-block (unsafe for RAW). The check_loop_carried_dependencies
    pass walks the dep_list this routine populates and applies these rules.

    O(N^2) PAIRWISE CHECK:
    Each pair of accesses is checked independently; the analysis budgets up
    to a quadratic-in-accesses cost for the precision it gains over the
    cheaper "any two stores alias if bases are unequal" approximation. In
    practice loops have fewer than 10 memory accesses, so N^2 is tractable.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The pair-iteration j = i+1 to access_count avoids checking each pair twice
    and avoids the symmetric A->A self-check. The dependency direction is
    canonically i (earlier instruction) -> j (later instruction) in
    program-source order, which matches the RAW/WAR/WAW naming convention.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(N^2 * D) where N is the number of memory accesses in the loop and D is
    the cost of one check_memory_dependency call (typically O(1) due to the
    early base-pointer alias test). For N=8 this is 28 calls per loop, which
    is negligible compared to the rest of the pass.
    @End Performance_Hints

    If context_ptr is equal to 0 or loop_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let header_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 0
    Let memory_accesses_dict be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72
    Let dependencies_dict be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 80

    Note: Get memory accesses for this loop
    Let access_list be proc get from Dictionary with memory_accesses_dict, header_id
    If access_list is equal to 0:
        Note: No memory accesses in loop
        Return 1
    End If

    Let access_count be proc length from List with access_list
    If access_count is less than 2:
        Note: Need at least 2 accesses for dependencies
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Create dependency list for this loop
    Let dep_list be proc create from List

    Note: Check all pairs of memory accesses for dependencies
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than access_count:
        Let access_i be proc get from List with access_list, i
        Let j be i plus 1

        While j is less than access_count:
            Let access_j be proc get from List with access_list, j

            Note: Check if there's a dependency between access_i and access_j
            Let dep_info be proc check_memory_dependency with context_ptr, loop_info, access_i, access_j

            If dep_info is not equal to 0:
                Note: Dependency found, add to list
                proc list_append from ListCore with dep_list, dep_info

                Let dep_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dep_info, 16
                Let is_loop_carried be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dep_info, 32

                Display "analyze_loop_dependencies: found dependency type "
                Display dep_type
                Display ", loop-carried: "
                Display is_loop_carried
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Store dependency list in dictionary
    proc set from Dictionary with dependencies_dict, header_id, dep_list

    Let dep_count be proc length from List with dep_list
    Display "analyze_loop_dependencies: found "
    Display dep_count
    Display " dependencies"

    Return dep_count
End Process

Process called "check_memory_dependency" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer, access_i as Integer, access_j as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Tests a pair of memory accesses for a data dependency and, when one
    exists, constructs the DependencyInfo record that downstream legality
    checks consume.

    PAIR CLASSIFICATION:
    1. ALIAS PROBE: if the two accesses have provably different base
       pointers, return 0 (no dependency). The current implementation uses
       SSA value equality as a fast must-not-alias test; full alias analysis
       (TBAA, restrict propagation) would tighten this.
    2. ACCESS-KIND PAIRING (gates dependency type):
         load,  load  -> no dep (return 0)
         store, load  -> RAW (type 1)
         load,  store -> WAR (type 2)
         store, store -> WAW (type 3)
    3. DISTANCE: compute_dependency_distance derives the iteration-count
       separation between the two accesses' index expressions.
    4. CLASSIFICATION: is_loop_carried = (distance > 0); can_privatize for
       WAR/WAW; can_runtime_check when distance is unknown (allows the
       vectorizer to emit a runtime alias check guard).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The conservative default is "assume may alias" when the base-pointer
    equality test is inconclusive; this is the standard "safe but
    potentially pessimistic" choice that preserves correctness while a more
    precise alias analyzer is integrated. The analysis_confidence field
    (currently fixed at 50 for inferred dependencies) lets future passes
    distinguish provable dependencies (confidence 100) from inferred ones
    that may be revisable by stronger analyses.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope
    A false negative (returning 0 when a real dependency exists) is the
    only correctness-affecting failure mode here; it would let
    check_loop_carried_dependencies green-light an unsafe vectorization.
    The base-pointer alias test is therefore biased pessimistically: when
    in doubt, treat the pair as potentially dependent.
    @End Security_Scope

    If access_i is equal to 0 or access_j is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get access properties
    Let base_i be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with access_i, 8
    Let base_j be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with access_j, 8
    Let index_i be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with access_i, 16
    Let index_j be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with access_j, 16
    Let is_load_i be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with access_i, 40
    Let is_load_j be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with access_j, 40
    Let is_store_i be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with access_i, 48
    Let is_store_j be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with access_j, 48

    Note: Check if accesses may alias (same base address)
    If base_i is not equal to base_j:
        Note: Different base pointers, no dependency (conservative: assume may alias)
        Note: For production: use alias analysis
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Determine dependency type
    Let dep_type be 0

    If is_store_i is equal to 1 and is_load_j is equal to 1:
        Set dep_type to 1  Note: RAW (Read After Write)
    End If

    If is_load_i is equal to 1 and is_store_j is equal to 1:
        Set dep_type to 2  Note: WAR (Write After Read)
    End If

    If is_store_i is equal to 1 and is_store_j is equal to 1:
        Set dep_type to 3  Note: WAW (Write After Write)
    End If

    If is_load_i is equal to 1 and is_load_j is equal to 1:
        Note: Load-Load, no dependency
        Return 0
    End If

    If dep_type is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Analyze dependency distance
    Let distance be proc compute_dependency_distance with context_ptr, loop_info, index_i, index_j

    Note: Allocate DependencyInfo structure (72 bytes)
    Let dep_info be proc allocate from Layout with 72
    If dep_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dep_info, 0, access_i
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dep_info, 8, access_j
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dep_info, 16, dep_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dep_info, 24, distance

    Note: Determine if loop-carried (distance > 0)
    Let is_loop_carried be 0
    If distance is greater than 0:
        Set is_loop_carried to 1
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dep_info, 32, is_loop_carried

    Note: Check if can be privatized (WAR and WAW can be)
    Let can_privatize be 0
    If dep_type is greater than 1:  Note: WAR or WAW
        Set can_privatize to 1
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dep_info, 40, can_privatize

    Note: Runtime check possible if distance is unknown
    Let can_runtime_check be 0
    If distance is equal to 0:  Note: Unknown distance
        Set can_runtime_check to 1
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dep_info, 48, can_runtime_check

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dep_info, 56, 0 Note: proven_independent (no)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dep_info, 64, 50 Note: analysis_confidence (50%)

    Return dep_info
End Process

Process called "compute_dependency_distance" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer, index_i as Integer, index_j as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes the iteration-count separation between two memory-access index
    expressions that share a base. This is the "distance" component of the
    classical dependency direction vector used by Wolfe and Banerjee
    dependency tests.

    DISTANCE INTERPRETATION:
    For accesses A_i and A_j writing/reading a[i + offset_i] and
    a[i + offset_j] respectively in the same iteration i, the distance is
    offset_j - offset_i: it tells us how many iterations apart in the
    abstract iteration space the two accesses fall.

      distance == 0 : same iteration. Safe under vectorization because the
                      dependency is satisfied within a single SIMD lane.
      distance > 0  : forward dependency (j after i in source order accesses
                      a later iteration). Whether this is safe depends on
                      whether the distance fits within VF (cross-lane within
                      same vector register is unsafe; cross-VF-block is
                      safe).
      distance unknown (returned as 0): the analyzer could not determine the
                      offsets; the caller must conservatively assume the
                      dependency is loop-carried.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Each index value is decomposed via extract_index_offset into an integer
    offset relative to the loop's primary IV. The sentinel value -999999
    signals "could not decompose"; in that case we fall back to distance 0
    (which is then treated conservatively by the safety check). Negative
    raw distances are clamped to 0 because a negative distance means the
    iteration order is reversed and is handled by the same lane-local rule.
    @End Implementation

    Let ssa_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 8
    Let induction_var be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 32

    Note: Check if indices are induction variable + constant offset
    Let offset_i be proc extract_index_offset with ssa_ptr, index_i, induction_var
    Let offset_j be proc extract_index_offset with ssa_ptr, index_j, induction_var

    If offset_i is equal to -999999 or offset_j is equal to -999999:
        Note: Cannot determine offsets, assume unknown distance
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Distance is the difference in offsets
    Let distance be offset_j minus offset_i

    If distance is less than 0:
        Set distance to 0  Note: Negative distance treated as 0 (same iteration)
    End If

    Return distance
End Process

Process called "extract_index_offset" that takes ssa_ptr as Integer, index_value as Integer, induction_var as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decomposes an array index value of the form IV + constant_offset into
    its constant component. Used by compute_dependency_distance to compare
    two indices that both reference the same induction variable.

    PATTERN RECOGNIZED:
      index == IV               -> offset = 0
      index == ADD(IV, c)        -> offset = c
      index == ADD(c, IV)        -> offset = c
      anything else              -> -999999 (sentinel for "indeterminate")
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single-level def-chain probe. Does not chase chained ADDs (e.g.,
    ADD(ADD(IV, 1), 2)) - those should already have been canonicalized to a
    single ADD with a folded constant by the constant-folding pass that
    runs before vectorization. The sentinel -999999 is chosen to be safely
    out of range for any realistic array offset; callers test against the
    exact sentinel value rather than a sign or magnitude.
    @End Implementation

    If index_value is equal to induction_var:
        Note: Direct use of induction variable, offset = 0
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if index is ADD(induction_var, constant)
    Let def_inst be proc get_defining_instruction from SSA with ssa_ptr, index_value
    If def_inst is equal to 0:
        Return -999999
    End If

    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with def_inst
    If opcode is not equal to 20100:  Note: MIR_ADD
        Return -999999
    End If

    Let left_operand be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 16
    Let right_operand be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 24

    If left_operand is equal to induction_var:
        Let is_const be proc is_constant from SSA with ssa_ptr, right_operand
        If is_const is equal to 1:
            Let offset be proc get_constant_value from SSA with ssa_ptr, right_operand
            Return offset
        End If
    End If

    If right_operand is equal to induction_var:
        Set is_const to proc is_constant from SSA with ssa_ptr, left_operand
        If is_const is equal to 1:
            Set offset to proc get_constant_value from SSA with ssa_ptr, left_operand
            Return offset
        End If
    End If

    Return -999999
End Process

Process called "check_loop_carried_dependencies" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The legality gate for vectorization. Walks the loop's dependency list and
    returns 1 (safe) only if every dependency is compatible with parallel
    cross-iteration execution.

    SAFETY RULES BY DEPENDENCY TYPE:
    - RAW + loop-carried + distance 1..VF-1: FATAL. The vector-lane
      interpretation would have an earlier iteration's write appear in a
      later iteration's read within the same SIMD register, which violates
      the semantics. Vectorization is rejected.
    - RAW + same iteration (distance 0): SAFE. The dependency is satisfied
      within a single lane (lane-local data flow).
    - WAR / WAW + loop-carried + can_privatize: SAFE. SSA renaming or scalar
      privatization removes the false dependency before vectorization.
    - WAR / WAW + loop-carried + NOT can_privatize: FATAL. The aliased
      storage cannot be split per-iteration, so the cross-iteration write
      ordering must be preserved.

    The proven_independent flag (set by future alias analysis improvements
    or by user-supplied __restrict-style annotations) overrides the
    conservative pair-wise classification.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single pass over the per-loop dep_list. Early-return on first fatal
    dependency for fast rejection of obviously unsafe loops.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope
    This is the legality gate; an incorrectly permissive answer here would
    cause vectorization of a loop with a real cross-iteration data race,
    producing silently wrong vector code at runtime. The conservative
    fallback (return 0, do not vectorize) is therefore the safe default for
    any dependency the analyzer cannot fully classify.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let header_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 0
    Let dependencies_dict be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 80

    Let dep_list be proc get from Dictionary with dependencies_dict, header_id
    If dep_list is equal to 0:
        Note: No dependencies, safe to vectorize
        Return 1
    End If

    Let dep_count be proc length from List with dep_list
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than dep_count:
        Let dep_info be proc get from List with dep_list, i
        Let dep_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dep_info, 16
        Let is_loop_carried be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dep_info, 32
        Let can_privatize be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dep_info, 40

        Note: Loop-carried RAW dependency prevents vectorization
        If dep_type is equal to 1 and is_loop_carried is equal to 1:
            Display "check_loop_carried_dependencies: loop-carried RAW dependency found"
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Loop-carried WAR/WAW can be handled with privatization
        If is_loop_carried is equal to 1 and can_privatize is equal to 0:
            Display "check_loop_carried_dependencies: unprivatizable loop-carried dependency"
            Return 0
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: No blocking dependencies
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MEMORY ACCESS PATTERN ANALYSIS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "collect_memory_accesses" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Walks the loop body and materializes a MemoryAccess record for every load
    and store instruction. The output drives all subsequent legality and
    profitability decisions: dependency analysis enumerates pairs of these
    records, alignment analysis indexes into them, and the cost model counts
    them by class (consecutive vs. strided vs. gather).

    PER-ACCESS METADATA CAPTURED:
    - Base address (the loop-invariant pointer or array origin)
    - Index value (the per-iteration offset, usually an affine function of IV)
    - Stride class (1 = unit-consecutive, k = k-strided, 0 = unknown)
    - Element size (in bytes; drives lane-count selection)
    - Alignment (in bytes; determines aligned vs. unaligned vector access)
    - is_consecutive flag (fast path for plain VLOAD/VSTORE)
    - is_loop_invariant_address flag (allows hoisting; address compute can
      be sunk out of the loop entirely)
    - depends_on list (populated later by dependency analysis)

    The collection is per-loop, not per-function: nested loops will run
    collect_memory_accesses separately for the inner and outer loops, with
    separate access lists keyed by header_id in the context's
    memory_accesses dictionary.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Iterates every block in body_blocks, then every instruction in each
    block. Instructions are classified by MIR opcode: MIR_LOAD (20201) and
    MIR_STORE (20200). Each matching instruction is handed to
    analyze_memory_access, which produces the MemoryAccess record. The
    record is then appended to the per-loop access list and the loop's
    memory_accesses_count is incremented.

    BLOCK-LIST DESTRUCTION ORDER:
    body_blocks is a Set; we materialize it as a List for iteration order,
    iterate, then destroy the List (not the Set - the Set is owned by
    loop_info and remains live).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(B * I) where B is the number of blocks in the loop body and I is the
    average instruction count per block. The per-instruction work
    (analyze_memory_access) is O(1) amortized.
    @End Performance_Hints

    If context_ptr is equal to 0 or loop_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let header_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 0
    Let body_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16
    Let memory_accesses_dict be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72

    Note: Create list for memory accesses in this loop
    Let access_list be proc create from List

    Note: Scan all blocks in loop body
    Let body_list be proc to_list from Set with body_blocks
    Let body_count be proc length from List with body_list
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than body_count:
        Let block_id be proc get from List with body_list, i
        Let block_ptr be proc get_block from CFG with cfg_ptr, block_id

        If block_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Note: Get instructions in block
            Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from CFG with block_ptr

            If instructions is not equal to 0:
                Let inst_count be proc length from List with instructions
                Let j be 0

                While j is less than inst_count:
                    Let inst_ptr be proc get from List with instructions, j
                    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst_ptr

                    Note: Check if load or store
                    If opcode is equal to 20201 or opcode is equal to 20200:  Note: MIR_LOAD or MIR_STORE
                        Note: Create MemoryAccess structure
                        Let mem_access be proc analyze_memory_access with context_ptr, loop_info, inst_ptr

                        If mem_access is not equal to 0:
                            proc list_append from ListCore with access_list, mem_access
                        End If
                    End If

                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While

                proc destroy from List with instructions
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc destroy from List with body_list

    Note: Store access list in dictionary
    proc set from Dictionary with memory_accesses_dict, header_id, access_list

    Let access_count be proc length from List with access_list

    Note: Update memory_accesses_count in loop_info
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 96, access_count

    Display "collect_memory_accesses: found "
    Display access_count
    Display " memory accesses"

    Return access_count
End Process

Process called "analyze_memory_access" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer, inst_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decomposes a single load/store instruction into its vectorization-relevant
    components and packages the result as a MemoryAccess record.

    DECOMPOSITION STEPS:
    1. Extract the address operand from the load (operand 0) or store
       (operand 0 = address, operand 1 = value).
    2. Split the address into base + index via extract_array_index. The
       canonical pattern is ADD(base, MUL(index, element_size)) for
       array[i] indexing.
    3. Classify the index expression's stride relative to the loop's primary
       IV via compute_access_stride.
    4. Look up the element type from the MIR type table and compute its size
       in bytes - this drives both alignment requirements and lane count.
    5. Compute the provable static alignment of the address via
       compute_alignment.
    6. Mark is_consecutive when stride == 1 - this is the fast path for
       plain vector loads/stores.
    7. Test whether the address is loop-invariant: invariant addresses can
       be hoisted entirely out of the loop and load just once, then the
       loaded value is broadcast to all lanes.

    All of these per-access facts feed downstream into dependency analysis,
    cost modeling, and the final transform.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The MIR load and store opcodes have different operand layouts:
      MIR_LOAD opcode 20201: result equals load of address; address is at
        operand 0, result type is at offset 32 of the node.
      MIR_STORE opcode 20200: store of address and value; address is at
        operand 0 at offset 8 of the node, value at offset 16, value type
        at offset 32.
    The opcode check picks the correct address slot for the dispatch.
    @End Implementation

    If inst_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst_ptr

    Note: Allocate MemoryAccess structure (88 bytes)
    Let mem_access be proc allocate from Layout with 88
    If mem_access is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set instruction pointer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with mem_access, 0, inst_ptr

    Note: Extract base address and index
    Let address_value be 0
    If opcode is equal to 20201:  Note: MIR_LOAD
        Set address_value to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 16
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20200:  Note: MIR_STORE
        Set address_value to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 8
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with mem_access, 8, address_value

    Note: Decompose address into base + index
    Let ssa_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 8
    Let index_value be proc extract_array_index with ssa_ptr, address_value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with mem_access, 16, index_value

    Note: Compute stride relative to induction variable
    Let induction_var be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 32
    Let stride be proc compute_access_stride with ssa_ptr, index_value, induction_var
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with mem_access, 24, stride

    Note: Get element size from type information
    Let element_type be 0
    If opcode is equal to 20201:  Note: MIR_LOAD
        Set element_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 32
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20200:  Note: MIR_STORE
        Set element_type to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 32
    End If

    Let element_size be 8  Note: Default 8 bytes
    If element_type is not equal to 0:
        Set element_size to proc get_type_size from MIR with element_type
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with mem_access, 32, element_size

    Note: Set is_load and is_store flags
    Let is_load be 0
    Let is_store be 0
    If opcode is equal to 20201:
        Set is_load to 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to 20200:
        Set is_store to 1
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with mem_access, 40, is_load
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with mem_access, 48, is_store

    Note: Compute alignment
    Let alignment be proc compute_alignment with context_ptr, address_value, element_size
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with mem_access, 56, alignment

    Note: Check if consecutive access (stride == 1)
    Let is_consecutive be 0
    If stride is equal to 1:
        Set is_consecutive to 1
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with mem_access, 64, is_consecutive

    Note: Check if address is loop-invariant
    Let is_invariant be proc is_loop_invariant_address with context_ptr, loop_info, address_value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with mem_access, 72, is_invariant

    Note: Create empty depends_on list
    Let depends_on be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with mem_access, 80, depends_on

    Return mem_access
End Process

Process called "extract_array_index" that takes ssa_ptr as Integer, address_value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decomposes a load/store address into base + index * element_size form and
    returns the index value. This is the canonical shape of an array indexing
    expression emitted by the frontend and the GEP-lowering pass:

        address = ADD(base, MUL(index, element_size))

    If the pattern matches, the returned value is the SSA value ID of the
    index. If the pattern is degenerate (no MUL inside the ADD), the right
    operand of the ADD is returned as a best-effort index. If the address
    is not even an ADD (e.g., a direct alloca pointer or a constant
    address), the address itself is returned and the access is classified
    as having zero-stride / loop-invariant index.

    The returned index value feeds compute_access_stride, which classifies
    it as IV, IV+c, IV*c, or unknown.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Two-level def-chain probe (ADD then MUL). Does not normalize commutative
    operand order - the frontend always emits MUL(index, element_size) with
    the index first, so the simple "right operand is MUL" check suffices.
    @End Implementation

    Let def_inst be proc get_defining_instruction from SSA with ssa_ptr, address_value
    If def_inst is equal to 0:
        Return address_value
    End If

    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with def_inst

    Note: Check for ADD(base, offset)
    If opcode is equal to 20100:  Note: MIR_ADD
        Let left_operand be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 16
        Let right_operand be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 24

        Note: Check if right operand is MUL(index, element_size)
        Let right_def be proc get_defining_instruction from SSA with ssa_ptr, right_operand
        If right_def is not equal to 0:
            Let right_opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with right_def
            If right_opcode is equal to 20102:  Note: MIR_MUL
                Let mul_left be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with right_def, 16
                Return mul_left  Note: This is the index
            End If
        End If

        Note: : just return right operand as index
        Return right_operand
    End If

    Return address_value
End Process

Process called "compute_access_stride" that takes ssa_ptr as Integer, index_value as Integer, induction_var as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Classifies the iteration-to-iteration stride of an array index expression
    relative to the loop's primary induction variable. The stride determines
    which class of vector memory instruction will be emitted:

      stride ==  1  : unit-stride consecutive access. Lane i loads element
                      i, lane i+1 loads element i+1, ..., as a single
                      contiguous SIMD register. Emitted as VLOAD/VSTORE.
                      This is the throughput-optimal case.
      stride == -1  : reverse-unit-stride. Emitted as VLOAD/VSTORE plus a
                      shuffle that reverses lane order (or, on architectures
                      with a "reverse load" - ARM SVE LD1RD - directly).
      stride ==  k  : strided access. Different lanes touch addresses
       (k > 1 or     base + k*0, base + k*1, ..., base + k*(VF-1). On most
        k < -1)      ISAs this degrades to a gather (loads) or scatter
                      (stores). Profitability depends on k - for k=2 the
                      gather is often still profitable; for k>=4 it usually
                      isn't.
      stride ==  0  : unknown stride. The index expression is too complex
                      for the static analyzer to classify. The vectorizer
                      either rejects the loop or falls back to runtime-
                      check-guarded vectorization.

    RECOGNIZED PATTERNS:
    The analyzer recognizes two index forms that arise from typical array
    indexing:
      1. index = IV                  (stride 1; direct loop counter)
      2. index = IV * c, c constant  (stride c; e.g., 2-byte stride for
                                      stepping through alternating
                                      elements of a struct array)
      3. index = IV + c, c constant  (stride 1; offset-from-IV, equivalent
                                      to a base-pointer shift)

    Affine combinations (a * IV + b * J + c) for nested loops are NOT
    classified here; they are a future extension that requires a tuple-IV
    representation and an SCEV-style symbolic evaluator.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Pattern matching is by direct MIR opcode test on the defining instruction
    of the index value. MUL with an IV operand and a constant operand yields
    the constant as stride. ADD with an IV operand and any constant offset
    operand yields stride 1 (the offset shifts the base address, not the
    stride). Any other defining-instruction shape produces the conservative
    "unknown" answer 0, which causes the caller to either reject the loop or
    fall back to a runtime check.
    @End Implementation

    If index_value is equal to induction_var:
        Note: Direct use of induction variable: stride = 1
        Return 1
    End If

    Let def_inst be proc get_defining_instruction from SSA with ssa_ptr, index_value
    If def_inst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with def_inst

    Note: Check for index = induction_var * constant
    If opcode is equal to 20102:  Note: MIR_MUL
        Let left_operand be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 16
        Let right_operand be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 24

        If left_operand is equal to induction_var:
            Let is_const be proc is_constant from SSA with ssa_ptr, right_operand
            If is_const is equal to 1:
                Let stride_value be proc get_constant_value from SSA with ssa_ptr, right_operand
                Return stride_value
            End If
        End If

        If right_operand is equal to induction_var:
            Set is_const to proc is_constant from SSA with ssa_ptr, left_operand
            If is_const is equal to 1:
                Set stride_value to proc get_constant_value from SSA with ssa_ptr, left_operand
                Return stride_value
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for index = induction_var + constant (still stride 1)
    If opcode is equal to 20100:  Note: MIR_ADD
        Set left_operand to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 16
        Set right_operand to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 24

        If left_operand is equal to induction_var or right_operand is equal to induction_var:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Unknown stride
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "compute_alignment" that takes context_ptr as Integer, address_value as Integer, element_size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Determines the provable static alignment (in bytes) of a memory address used
    inside a candidate vectorizable loop. Alignment is the single biggest
    determinant of vector load/store throughput on every modern ISA:

    - x86: aligned MOVAPS/MOVAPD on a misaligned address #GP-faults pre-AVX,
      and even with the modern relaxed-alignment encodings (MOVUPS) misaligned
      access can split across cache lines, costing 2x bandwidth.
    - ARM NEON: VLD1 with .align 128 is faster than the unaligned form and
      avoids the alignment fault on strict-alignment cores.
    - RISC-V V: unaligned vector access is permitted but may trap to the kernel
      on cores without the Zicclsm extension, costing thousands of cycles.

    The vectorizer uses this value to decide between:
    1. Plain aligned vector load/store - when alignment >= VF * element_size.
    2. Unaligned vector load/store (slightly slower, no peeling) - when
       alignment < VF * element_size but the architecture supports unaligned.
    3. Loop versioning with alignment peeling - emit a scalar prelude that
       iterates until the address is VF-aligned, then enter the aligned hot
       loop. Used when the unaligned penalty is high and peeling is profitable.

    ANALYSIS STRATEGY:
    Currently the analysis chases the SSA def-chain to find an alloca, whose
    declared alignment is an upper bound. Future extensions should also
    recognize aligned-allocation library calls (posix_memalign, aligned_alloc,
    operator new with std::align_val_t) and propagate known-alignment metadata
    through pointer arithmetic by computing GCD(known_align, constant_offset).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Results are cached in the per-context alignment_cache dictionary keyed by
    SSA value ID. Cache hits are O(1); misses do at most one SSA def-chain hop
    and one MIR-node-opcode read. The default conservative answer is the
    element size, which is always a safe lower bound because the type system
    guarantees that an in-bounds pointer of type T is aligned to at least
    the alignment of T.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Alignment underestimation never breaks correctness - it only causes the
    vectorizer to emit unaligned vector loads or skip vectorization. Alignment
    overestimation, however, is a correctness bug (would emit an aligned load
    that faults at runtime). The cache must therefore only ever store provably
    lower-bound alignment values; runtime alignment assertions are not used to
    populate the cache.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    This analysis directly influences emitted instruction encodings. An
    incorrectly high cached alignment value would cause the backend to emit
    aligned vector accesses that fault on misaligned runtime data, which can
    be exploited as a denial-of-service vector if attacker-controlled pointer
    arithmetic flows in. The cache is therefore populated only from
    statically provable sources (alloca declarations, allocation-site
    annotations), never from runtime tests.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let alignment_cache be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 96

    Note: Check cache first
    Let cached_alignment be proc get from Dictionary with alignment_cache, address_value
    If cached_alignment is not equal to 0:
        Return cached_alignment
    End If

    Note: Analyze address computation for alignment information
    Let ssa_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 8
    Let def_inst be proc get_defining_instruction from SSA with ssa_ptr, address_value

    Let computed_alignment be element_size  Note: Default: aligned to element size

    If def_inst is not equal to 0:
        Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with def_inst

        Note: If address is alloca, check alloca alignment
        If opcode is equal to 20200:  Note: MIR_ALLOCA
            Let alloca_alignment be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 32
            If alloca_alignment is greater than computed_alignment:
                Set computed_alignment to alloca_alignment
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Cache alignment
    proc set from Dictionary with alignment_cache, address_value, computed_alignment

    Return computed_alignment
End Process

Process called "is_loop_invariant_address" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer, address_value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Tests whether an address SSA value is loop-invariant - i.e., produces the
    same value across all iterations. A loop-invariant address allows the
    address computation to be hoisted out of the loop entirely (LICM
    territory) and lets the vectorizer recognize the "splat" / "broadcast"
    pattern: a single load before the loop fills every lane of the vector
    register with the same value, eliminating a per-iteration memory
    transaction.

    INVARIANCE CRITERIA:
    - Values defined outside the function (e.g., function arguments) are
      trivially invariant.
    - Values defined in a block outside the loop body are invariant within
      this loop.
    - Values defined inside the loop body are non-invariant (they may
      change per iteration).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Locates the defining instruction's block via SSA.get_instruction_block
    and tests membership in the loop's body_blocks set. The conservative
    default (when the def cannot be located) is "invariant", because a
    missing def usually indicates an SSA-import from outside the current
    analysis scope.
    @End Implementation

    Let ssa_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 8
    Let def_inst be proc get_defining_instruction from SSA with ssa_ptr, address_value

    If def_inst is equal to 0:
        Note: Defined outside function, must be invariant
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Check if defining instruction is in loop body
    Let body_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16
    Let def_block be proc get_instruction_block from SSA with ssa_ptr, def_inst

    Let in_loop be proc contains from Set with body_blocks, def_block

    If in_loop is equal to 0:
        Note: Defined outside loop, invariant
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Defined inside loop, not invariant
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: COST MODELING AND PROFITABILITY ANALYSIS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "compute_vectorization_cost" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decides whether vectorizing a legal loop is actually profitable. Legality
    (proven by the dependency analysis) is necessary but not sufficient -
    vectorization adds prologue (alignment peel, min-trip-count check),
    epilogue (modulo-VF remainder), and possibly horizontal-reduce overhead.
    A short trip count, or a body dominated by non-vectorizable scalar tails
    (function calls, indirect-control-flow), can easily make the vector version
    slower than the scalar version.

    COST MODEL FORMULATION:
    The cost model is a coarse static estimator suitable for an MIR pass that
    runs before register allocation:

        scalar_cost     = sum over body of per-op-scalar-cycles
        vector_cost     = (vectorizable_ops / VF) + non_vectorizable_ops
                        + (memory_ops_consecutive / VF) * mem_cycle_cost
                        + (memory_ops_strided)         * gather_scatter_cost
        overhead        = prologue_cost + epilogue_cost + alignment_peel_cost
        speedup_ratio   = scalar_cost / (vector_cost + overhead)

    The ratio is stored as fixed-point (scaled by 100) so the comparison
    against the profitability threshold (default 1.2x = 120) can be done in
    pure integer arithmetic. Loops below the threshold are rejected and fall
    through to the scalar code path.

    LANE-WIDTH SELECTION INTERACTION:
    This pass currently uses the target_vector_width chosen at context
    creation. A more sophisticated future cost model would explore multiple VF
    values (e.g., 4, 8, 16) and pick the maximum profitable one, since wider
    vectors amortize overhead better at the cost of larger remainder loops and
    potentially worse register pressure. The cost model's interface (storing
    scalar_cost and vector_cost separately) makes this extension non-breaking.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Memory operations are double-counted in the scalar_cost (added with a 4x
    cycle weight) because L1 cache hits cost ~4 cycles on most architectures,
    while register-register arithmetic costs 1 cycle. This 4:1 ratio is
    deliberately conservative - in practice memory throughput dominates for
    bandwidth-bound loops, so over-weighting memory in scalar_cost slightly
    biases the heuristic in favor of vectorization for memory-heavy loops,
    which is exactly the workload where vectorization gives the largest
    speedup.

    Function calls (opcodes 20304/20305) are classified as non-vectorizable
    because the calling convention's register-bank assumptions break with
    vector arguments unless the callee is itself a vector intrinsic. Future
    work: extend the call classifier to recognize vector-clone candidates
    (similar to GCC's #pragma omp declare simd) and inline them as vector ops
    when the speedup justifies the analysis cost.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    The cost model walks the loop body once and is O(I) in body instruction
    count. It is called once per legal loop, so for typical functions with
    fewer than 10 loops the cost-modeling overhead is well under 1% of the
    overall pass time.
    @End Performance_Hints

    If context_ptr is equal to 0 or loop_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let header_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 0
    Let body_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16
    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let memory_accesses_dict be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72

    Note: Allocate CostModel structure (88 bytes)
    Let cost_model be proc allocate from Layout with 88
    If cost_model is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Count operations in loop body
    Let vector_ops be 0
    Let scalar_ops be 0
    Let memory_ops be 0

    Let body_list be proc to_list from Set with body_blocks
    Let body_count be proc length from List with body_list
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than body_count:
        Let block_id be proc get from List with body_list, i
        Let block_ptr be proc get_block from CFG with cfg_ptr, block_id

        If block_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from CFG with block_ptr

            If instructions is not equal to 0:
                Let inst_count be proc length from List with instructions
                Let j be 0

                While j is less than inst_count:
                    Let inst_ptr be proc get from List with instructions, j
                    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst_ptr

                    Note: Classify instruction
                    If opcode is greater than or equal to 20100 and opcode is less than or equal to 20115:
                        Set vector_ops to vector_ops plus 1  Note: Arithmetic ops vectorizable
                    End If

                    If opcode is equal to 20200 or opcode is equal to 20201:
                        Set memory_ops to memory_ops plus 1
                    End If

                    If opcode is equal to 20304 or opcode is equal to 20305:
                        Set scalar_ops to scalar_ops plus 1  Note: Function calls not vectorizable
                    End If

                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While

                proc destroy from List with instructions
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc destroy from List with body_list

    Note: Store operation counts
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cost_model, 40, vector_ops
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cost_model, 48, scalar_ops
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cost_model, 56, memory_ops

    Note: Estimate costs ( cost model)
    Let vector_width be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 120

    Note: Scalar cost: operations * cycles per operation
    Let scalar_cost be (vector_ops plus scalar_ops) multiplied by 1
    Set scalar_cost to scalar_cost plus (memory_ops multiplied by 4)  Note: Memory is expensive
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cost_model, 0, scalar_cost

    Note: Vector cost: vectorizable ops / width + scalar ops
    Let vector_arithmetic_cost be vector_ops divided by vector_width
    Let vector_memory_cost be memory_ops divided by vector_width
    Set vector_memory_cost to vector_memory_cost multiplied by 4

    Let vector_cost be vector_arithmetic_cost plus scalar_ops plus vector_memory_cost
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cost_model, 8, vector_cost

    Note: Overhead: prologue + epilogue
    Let overhead_cost be 10  Note: Fixed overhead estimate
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cost_model, 16, overhead_cost

    Note: Compute speedup ratio (higher is better)
    Let total_vector_cost be vector_cost plus overhead_cost
    Let speedup_ratio be 0

    If total_vector_cost is greater than 0:
        Set speedup_ratio to (scalar_cost multiplied by 100) divided by total_vector_cost
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cost_model, 24, speedup_ratio

    Note: Check profitability
    Let profitability_threshold be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 112
    Let is_profitable be 0

    If speedup_ratio is greater than or equal to profitability_threshold:
        Set is_profitable to 1
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cost_model, 32, is_profitable

    Note: Initialize remaining fields
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cost_model, 64, 0 Note: reduction_cost
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cost_model, 72, 0 Note: gather_scatter_cost
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cost_model, 80, 100 Note: estimated_trip_count

    Note: Store cost model
    Let cost_models_dict be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 88
    proc set from Dictionary with cost_models_dict, header_id, cost_model

    Display "compute_vectorization_cost: speedup ratio = "
    Display speedup_ratio
    Display "%, profitable = "
    Display is_profitable

    Return is_profitable
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: VECTORIZATION TRANSFORMATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "transform_loop_to_vector" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Performs the actual scalar-to-vector rewrite once a loop has passed all
    legality and profitability gates. The transformation widens iteration
    semantics by a factor of VF (the loop's chosen vector_factor): each scalar
    operation on element type T becomes one operation on a vector of VF
    Ts, the induction variable is stepped by VF * stride, and the loop trip
    count is effectively divided by VF.

    THREE-PHASE OUTPUT SHAPE (canonical vectorizer skeleton):
    1. Vector prologue: alignment check + min-trip-count check. If the runtime
       trip count is below VF, control branches directly to the scalar epilogue,
       avoiding any vector-body execution. If the base address is not aligned
       to (VF * element_size), a peeled scalar prelude (a small scalar loop
       running until alignment is achieved) is emitted - this is the standard
       "loop versioning for alignment" technique that lets us emit aligned
       vector loads instead of unaligned ones in the hot loop.
    2. Vector body: every vectorizable scalar instruction is replaced in place
       with its vector counterpart (vector_opcode = scalar_opcode + 400 in
       this MIR encoding). The induction variable's stride is rewritten to
       step by VF. Reductions are widened to vector accumulators with a
       horizontal-reduce epilogue.
    3. Scalar epilogue: the trip_count mod VF remainder iterations execute as
       the original scalar loop body, ensuring correctness for trip counts
       that are not exact multiples of VF.

    The prologue/epilogue scheme dominates LLVM's loop vectorizer output and is
    required for correctness whenever the trip count is unknown at compile time
    or known to not be a multiple of VF.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Failure of any phase (prologue creation, body vectorization, or epilogue
    creation) causes the transform to bail out before the CFG is mutated by
    update_loop_structure, so the original scalar loop remains correct. Stats
    counters (vectorized_loops, total_instructions_vectorized) are updated only
    after all four phases succeed.

    NOTE: This implementation does not yet perform mid-transform rollback if
    update_loop_structure fails after the body has been rewritten in place - a
    failure there would leave the function in an inconsistent state. In
    practice update_loop_structure failure paths are limited to CFG-edge
    integrity errors that signal a deeper compiler bug, so the pass aborts the
    whole compilation rather than attempting recovery.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    The pass is O(I) in the number of instructions in the loop body, plus
    O(E) for the CFG-edge rewiring in update_loop_structure where E is the
    number of loop-exit edges (usually 1 or 2). The dominant cost is typically
    the per-instruction lookup in collect_memory_accesses, not the transform
    itself.
    @End Performance_Hints

    If context_ptr is equal to 0 or loop_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Display "transform_loop_to_vector: transforming loop"

    Let header_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 0
    Let vector_factor be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 72
    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let ssa_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 8

    Note: Step 1: Create vector prologue block
    Let prologue_block be proc create_vector_prologue with context_ptr, loop_info
    If prologue_block is equal to 0:
        Display "transform_loop_to_vector: failed to create prologue"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 2: Transform loop body instructions to vector form
    Let body_transformed be proc vectorize_loop_body with context_ptr, loop_info, vector_factor
    If body_transformed is equal to 0:
        Display "transform_loop_to_vector: failed to vectorize body"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 3: Create scalar epilogue for remainder iterations
    Let epilogue_block be proc create_scalar_epilogue with context_ptr, loop_info
    If epilogue_block is equal to 0:
        Display "transform_loop_to_vector: failed to create epilogue"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 4: Update loop structure
    Let update_success be proc update_loop_structure with context_ptr, loop_info, prologue_block, epilogue_block
    If update_success is equal to 0:
        Display "transform_loop_to_vector: failed to update structure"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Update statistics
    Let vectorized_loops be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 32
    Set vectorized_loops to vectorized_loops plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 32, vectorized_loops

    Let instructions_vectorized be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 48
    Set instructions_vectorized to instructions_vectorized plus body_transformed
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 48, instructions_vectorized

    Display "transform_loop_to_vector: successfully vectorized loop with factor "
    Display vector_factor

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "create_vector_prologue" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Materializes the vector prologue block, which guards entry into the
    widened loop body. The prologue is the standard "loop versioning"
    construct used by every modern vectorizer (LLVM LoopVectorizer, GCC tree-
    vectorize) to make vectorization safe and efficient at runtime:

    PROLOGUE RESPONSIBILITIES:
    1. Minimum-trip-count guard: if the runtime trip count is below VF, jump
       directly to the scalar epilogue. Without this guard a vector loop
       executing zero iterations of its body would still execute its
       prologue overhead and any preamble setup, wasting work; worse, with
       trip counts under VF the vector body would never be entered, leaving
       all iterations to the scalar epilogue.
    2. Alignment peeling (when profitable): execute scalar iterations until
       the base address is VF-element-size aligned, then enter the aligned
       vector hot loop. This is the technique that lets us emit aligned
       VLOAD/VSTORE in the body instead of the slower unaligned variants.
       The peel count is computed as
           peel = (VF - (((uintptr_t)base / element_size) mod VF)) mod VF
    3. Runtime alias checks (when dependency analysis was inconclusive):
       compare the address ranges of any pair of accesses flagged
       can_runtime_check; if they overlap, jump to the scalar fallback.
       This lets us vectorize loops where alias analysis could not prove
       independence statically.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The current implementation allocates the prologue block ID and creates
    the empty basic block; instruction-level population of the alignment
    check, trip count guard, and any runtime alias checks happens after
    backend integration is complete. The block is wired into the CFG by
    update_loop_structure.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope
    The min-trip-count and alignment guards are correctness-critical: an
    incorrect guard would let the vector body execute on a too-short array
    or a misaligned address, producing an out-of-bounds read or an alignment
    fault. Future implementations must emit these checks with the same
    conservatism as the legality gates above - any guard the analyzer cannot
    statically prove redundant must be emitted at runtime.
    @End Security_Scope

    Display "create_vector_prologue: creating prologue block"

    Note: Create new basic block for prologue
    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let prologue_id be proc allocate_block_id from CFG with cfg_ptr
    Let prologue_block be proc create_mir_basic_block from MIR with prologue_id, 0

    Note: Add alignment check and trip count verification instructions
    Note: These ensure safe vectorization execution

    proc add_block_to_function from CFG with cfg_ptr, prologue_block

    Return prologue_id
End Process

Process called "vectorize_loop_body" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer, vector_factor as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Walks every instruction in the loop body and applies the appropriate
    scalar-to-vector widening transform. This is the heart of the
    transformation phase: after this routine returns, the loop body is
    expressed entirely in vector MIR opcodes, ready for the backend to
    select target-specific SIMD instructions.

    DISPATCH BY OPCODE CLASS:
    - Arithmetic ops (20100-20115: add/sub/mul/div/mod and friends):
      Widened via transform_to_vector_instruction. The opcode is rewritten
      to the vector form (scalar + 400) and the result type is bumped to
      a vector type with the loop's vector_factor lane count.
    - Memory ops (20200 = MIR_STORE, 20201 = MIR_LOAD):
      Widened via transform_to_vector_memory, which selects between
      consecutive vector load/store and gather/scatter based on the
      MemoryAccess.is_consecutive flag set during analysis.
    - Control flow, phis, calls, and other non-vectorizable opcodes are
      left untouched. The vectorizer model assumes that the loop body has
      no internal control flow except the IV update and the loop exit;
      stronger loops with internal branches must be flattened by
      if-conversion before reaching this pass.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Per-block, per-instruction loop. The instruction count returned
    (instructions_transformed) drives the
    context.total_instructions_vectorized statistic, which is used both for
    debug reporting and for the should-this-pass-run-again heuristic on
    nested optimization passes.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(I) in the number of body instructions. Per-instruction transformation
    is O(1). For a typical 10-instruction loop body, this routine returns
    in single-digit microseconds even on cold caches.
    @End Performance_Hints

    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let body_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16
    Let instructions_transformed be 0

    Let body_list be proc to_list from Set with body_blocks
    Let body_count be proc length from List with body_list
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than body_count:
        Let block_id be proc get from List with body_list, i
        Let block_ptr be proc get_block from CFG with cfg_ptr, block_id

        If block_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from CFG with block_ptr

            If instructions is not equal to 0:
                Let inst_count be proc length from List with instructions
                Let j be 0

                While j is less than inst_count:
                    Let inst_ptr be proc get from List with instructions, j
                    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst_ptr

                    Note: Transform vectorizable instructions
                    If opcode is greater than or equal to 20100 and opcode is less than or equal to 20115:
                        Note: Arithmetic operation, can be vectorized
                        Let transformed be proc transform_to_vector_instruction with context_ptr, inst_ptr, vector_factor
                        If transformed is equal to 1:
                            Set instructions_transformed to instructions_transformed plus 1
                        End If
                    End If

                    If opcode is equal to 20200 or opcode is equal to 20201:
                        Note: Memory operation, can be vectorized if consecutive
                        Set transformed to proc transform_to_vector_memory with context_ptr, loop_info, inst_ptr, vector_factor
                        If transformed is equal to 1:
                            Set instructions_transformed to instructions_transformed plus 1
                        End If
                    End If

                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While

                proc destroy from List with instructions
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc destroy from List with body_list

    Display "vectorize_loop_body: transformed "
    Display instructions_transformed
    Display " instructions"

    Return instructions_transformed
End Process

Process called "transform_to_vector_instruction" that takes context_ptr as Integer, inst_ptr as Integer, vector_factor as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Widens a scalar arithmetic MIR instruction into its SIMD counterpart. The
    transformation is purely lane-replication semantics: a single
    add/sub/mul/div on scalars becomes a single vadd/vsub/vmul/vdiv on
    vectors-of-VF, where every lane independently applies the original op to
    the corresponding lanes of the operands.

    OPCODE ENCODING:
    Vector opcodes are encoded as scalar_opcode + 400 in this MIR. The +400
    offset is reserved in the MIR opcode space (scalar arithmetic occupies
    20100-20115, vector arithmetic 20500-20515). This dense numeric encoding
    enables fast classification by the backend: a single range test
    distinguishes scalar from vector arithmetic, and the +400 shift can be
    eliminated by a single ADD to convert a scalar-handler dispatch into a
    vector-handler dispatch.

    LANE COUNT INVARIANT:
    Every operand and result of a vector instruction must have the same lane
    count (the loop's vector_factor). This function therefore updates the
    result value type via set_value_type_vector to mark the lane count.
    Operands keep their existing SSA value IDs; the SSA infrastructure
    upgrades them to vector type on first use, propagating the lane-count
    annotation backwards through the def chain. This delayed-widening keeps
    the per-instruction transform O(1) and lets a separate SSA-typing pass
    perform the per-value vectorization.

    NOT HANDLED HERE:
    - Reductions (sum, min, max accumulating across iterations) need a
      horizontal-reduce epilogue and are handled in vectorize_loop_body.
    - Type conversions (e.g., sext from i32 to i64) need lane-width adjustment
      and are emitted as separate vsext/vzext instructions.
    - Compares need a mask-producing form (vcmpeq -> mask register) that is
      conceptually distinct from a value-producing vector op; future work.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The transformation is purely in-place MIR-node mutation: opcode field
    overwrite + result type bump. No new instructions are created and no
    operand re-encoding is needed because the lane-count annotation lives on
    the value, not on the operand reference.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    This is the inner loop of body widening, called once per vectorizable
    instruction. Its O(1) cost is the reason the whole pass is dominated by
    analysis rather than transformation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst_ptr

    Display "transform_to_vector_instruction: transforming opcode "
    Display opcode
    Display " with factor "
    Display vector_factor

    Note: Modify instruction type to vector type
    Note: Update SSA value types to vector types
    Let vector_opcode be opcode plus 400  Note: Vector opcodes offset by 400
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 0, vector_opcode

    Note: Update result value type to vector type
    Let result_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 8
    If result_value is not equal to 0:
        Note: Mark value as vector type with given factor
        proc set_value_type_vector from MIR with result_value, vector_factor
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "transform_to_vector_memory" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer, inst_ptr as Integer, vector_factor as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Rewrites a scalar load or store into the appropriate vector memory
    instruction. Memory ops have richer dispatch than arithmetic ops because
    the access pattern determines which class of vector memory instruction is
    legal AND profitable:

    1. UNIT-STRIDE CONSECUTIVE (stride == 1):
       The fast path. Element i, i+1, ..., i+VF-1 of the array are loaded as
       a single contiguous SIMD register. Emitted as MIR_VLOAD/MIR_VSTORE
       (scalar opcode + 400 in the encoding). These map directly to a single
       ISA instruction on every modern SIMD: x86 MOVDQA/MOVDQU, ARM NEON
       LD1/ST1, RISC-V vle/vse, etc.

    2. NON-UNIT STRIDE (stride != 1, including reverse and gather/scatter):
       The slow but still-vectorizable path. Each lane loads from a different
       base + index[lane] address. Emitted as MIR_GATHER (load) or
       MIR_SCATTER (store). These map to x86 VPGATHER/VPSCATTER (AVX2+),
       ARM SVE/SVE2 LD1*-gather, and RISC-V V indexed-load. Throughput is
       typically 1/VF of a contiguous load because each lane is a separate
       memory transaction, but the vector version still wins over scalar
       when the body has substantial vectorizable arithmetic between the
       memory ops.

    Lane width (VF) selection has already been made by the cost model; this
    function is purely a translator from the MemoryAccess analysis result into
    the matching MIR opcode. The MemoryAccess.is_consecutive flag carries the
    classification produced by compute_access_stride.

    OPERAND LAYOUT FOR GATHER/SCATTER:
    Gather/scatter need an extra operand: the lane-indexed offset vector. The
    index_vector is stored in MemoryAccess.is_loop_invariant_address slot
    (field offset 72) during analysis and is appended to the instruction's
    operand array here, increasing operand_count by 1.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The function dispatches by searching the per-loop access list for the
    MemoryAccess record that matches inst_ptr. The lookup is linear because
    the access list is typically short (under 10 entries per loop). For
    pathologically long lists this could be lifted to a dictionary keyed by
    instruction pointer.

    The opcode-rewrite uses in-place mutation of the MIR node: opcode field
    is set to the vector form, and the result value type is updated to vector
    via set_value_type_vector. No new instructions are created; downstream
    passes see a structurally identical CFG with widened operand types.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Gather/scatter is significantly slower than consecutive access on most
    cores (Skylake-X VPGATHERDD: ~22 cycles vs. MOVDQA: 1 cycle). The cost
    model should already have rejected unprofitable gather-dominated loops by
    the time we get here, but a defensive secondary check at the call site
    would be a reasonable hardening - currently this function emits the
    gather/scatter form whenever the access is non-consecutive, deferring to
    the cost model for the profitability decision.
    @End Performance_Hints

    Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst_ptr

    Display "transform_to_vector_memory: transforming memory opcode "
    Display opcode
    Display " with factor "
    Display vector_factor

    Note: Check if memory access is consecutive (required for vector load/store)
    Let header_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 0
    Let memory_accesses_dict be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 72
    Let access_list be proc get from Dictionary with memory_accesses_dict, header_id

    If access_list is not equal to 0:
        Let access_count be proc length from List with access_list
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than access_count:
            Let mem_access be proc get from List with access_list, i
            Let access_inst be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mem_access, 0

            If access_inst is equal to inst_ptr:
                Note: Found matching access
                Let is_consecutive be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mem_access, 64

                If is_consecutive is equal to 1:
                    Note: Consecutive access - use standard vector load/store
                    Let vector_opcode be opcode plus 400  Note: VLOAD=20600, VSTORE=20601
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 0, vector_opcode

                    Note: Update result value to vector type
                    Let result_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 8
                    If result_value is not equal to 0:
                        proc set_value_type_vector from MIR with result_value, vector_factor
                    End If
                    Return 1
                Otherwise:
                    Note: Non-consecutive access - use gather/scatter instructions
                    Display "transform_to_vector_memory: using gather/scatter for non-consecutive access"

                    Note: Transform to gather (load) or scatter (store)
                    If opcode is equal to 20200:  Note: MIR_LOAD
                        Let gather_opcode be 20700  Note: MIR_GATHER
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 0, gather_opcode
                    Otherwise If opcode is equal to 20201:  Note: MIR_STORE
                        Let scatter_opcode be 20701  Note: MIR_SCATTER
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 0, scatter_opcode
                    End If

                    Note: Get index vector from memory access pattern
                    Let index_vector be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mem_access, 72

                    Note: Add index vector operand for gather/scatter
                    Note: Gather: result = gather(base_ptr, index_vector, mask)
                    Note: Scatter: scatter(base_ptr, index_vector, value, mask)
                    Let operands_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 24
                    Let operand_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 16

                    Note: Expand operands array to include index vector
                    Let new_operand_count be operand_count plus 1
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 16, new_operand_count

                    Note: Store index vector as additional operand
                    Let index_offset be operands_ptr plus (operand_count multiplied by 8)
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with index_offset, 0, index_vector

                    Note: Update result value to vector type
                    Set result_value to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 8
                    If result_value is not equal to 0:
                        proc set_value_type_vector from MIR with result_value, vector_factor
                    End If

                    Return 1
                End If
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "create_scalar_epilogue" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Materializes the scalar epilogue block, which executes the residual
    (trip_count mod VF) iterations after the vector body completes. Without
    the epilogue, a loop with trip count not exactly divisible by VF would
    either read out of bounds (if we naively rounded up) or skip its tail
    iterations (if we rounded down).

    EPILOGUE RESPONSIBILITIES:
    1. Execute the original scalar body for the remainder iterations (count
       in 0..VF-1). At most VF-1 scalar iterations run here, so the
       epilogue is small and rarely dominates loop runtime.
    2. Merge into the same exit point as the original scalar loop, so that
       phi nodes in the post-loop blocks see a single producer regardless
       of which path (vector body, vector prologue jump, scalar epilogue)
       reached them.

    The epilogue is also the target of the prologue's min-trip-count guard:
    a loop with fewer than VF iterations bypasses the vector body entirely
    and runs as pure scalar code via the epilogue. This is the standard
    "loop versioning" two-path layout used by modern vectorizers.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The block is allocated and registered with the CFG here; population
    with a copy of the original scalar body and wiring of the loop-exit phi
    fixups happens during update_loop_structure and the subsequent
    SSA-repair pass.
    @End Implementation

    Display "create_scalar_epilogue: creating epilogue block"

    Note: Create new basic block for epilogue
    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let epilogue_id be proc allocate_block_id from CFG with cfg_ptr
    Let epilogue_block be proc create_mir_basic_block from MIR with epilogue_id, 0

    Note: Epilogue will execute remainder iterations in scalar mode
    Note: CFG wiring handled by update_loop_structure

    proc add_block_to_function from CFG with cfg_ptr, epilogue_block

    Return epilogue_id
End Process

Process called "update_loop_structure" that takes context_ptr as Integer, loop_info as Integer, prologue_block as Integer, epilogue_block as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Performs the CFG-level surgery that splices the prologue and epilogue
    around the vectorized loop body, producing the canonical three-block
    vector-loop layout:

         preheader
            |
            v
         prologue   (alignment check, trip-count guard, runtime alias checks)
        /        \
       v          v
    vector_body   epilogue   (scalar remainder)
       |          ^
       +----------+

    EDGE REWIRING STEPS:
    1. Redirect preheader -> header to preheader -> prologue. The prologue
       is now the single entry into the vector region.
    2. Add prologue -> header to keep the vector body reachable.
    3. For every loop exit edge (body_block -> exit_target), redirect
       through the epilogue so that exit phi-nodes see a unified
       last-iteration producer.

    This wiring is intentionally conservative: every loop exit is routed
    through the epilogue, even when no scalar remainder is needed at
    runtime, so the SSA phi-fixup logic has a single canonical merge point
    regardless of trip count.

    PHI-NODE REPAIR:
    Header phi-nodes that previously named the preheader as a predecessor
    must be updated to name the prologue, because the preheader -> header
    edge has been redirected. This is done by find_or_create_preheader for
    the original preheader; the same logic applies here for the new
    prologue, and is performed during the SSA-repair pass that follows
    this routine.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Uses CFG.redirect_edge for in-place edge mutation and CFG.add_edge for
    new edges. Edge enumeration is via the body_blocks Set and the per-loop
    exit_blocks Set computed by compute_exit_blocks during loop info
    construction.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope
    Incorrect CFG rewiring would leave the function with dead vector code
    or, worse, a control-flow path that reaches an undefined block. The
    routine therefore never deletes edges - it only redirects existing
    edges and adds new ones, preserving the dominator tree's invariants
    for the post-loop blocks.
    @End Security_Scope

    Display "update_loop_structure: updating CFG edges"

    Let cfg_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 0
    Let header_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 0
    Let preheader_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 8
    Let exit_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 24

    Note: Wire CFG: preheader → prologue → header
    If preheader_id is not equal to 0:
        Note: Redirect preheader → header edge to preheader → prologue
        proc redirect_edge from CFG with cfg_ptr, preheader_id, header_id, prologue_block

        Note: Add prologue → header edge
        proc add_edge from CFG with cfg_ptr, prologue_block, header_id

        Display "update_loop_structure: wired preheader → prologue → header"
    End If

    Note: Wire loop exits to epilogue
    If exit_blocks is not equal to 0:
        Let exit_list be proc to_list from Set with exit_blocks
        Let exit_count be proc length from List with exit_list
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than exit_count:
            Let exit_id be proc get from List with exit_list, i

            Note: For each exit block, find loop body predecessors
            Let exit_preds be proc get_block_predecessors from CFG with cfg_ptr, exit_id
            If exit_preds is not equal to 0:
                Let body_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 16
                Let pred_count be proc length from List with exit_preds
                Let j be 0

                While j is less than pred_count:
                    Let pred_id be proc get from List with exit_preds, j

                    Note: If predecessor is in loop body, redirect to epilogue first
                    Let pred_in_loop be proc contains from Set with body_blocks, pred_id
                    If pred_in_loop is equal to 1:
                        proc redirect_edge from CFG with cfg_ptr, pred_id, exit_id, epilogue_block
                    End If

                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While

                proc destroy from List with exit_preds
            End If

            Note: Wire epilogue to original exit
            proc add_edge from CFG with cfg_ptr, epilogue_block, exit_id

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        proc destroy from List with exit_list

        Display "update_loop_structure: wired loop exits through epilogue"
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: VECTORIZATION PASS ENTRY POINTS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "optimize_function_with_vectorization" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Top-level driver for the loop auto-vectorization pass. Implements the classical
    "loop vectorizer" strategy used by LLVM and GCC: scalar loops whose iterations
    are provably independent are rewritten so that VF (vectorization factor)
    consecutive iterations execute as a single SIMD operation per lane, where VF
    matches the target SIMD register lane count (4 for SSE/NEON, 8 for AVX2,
    16 for AVX-512).

    PIPELINE STAGES:
    1. Natural loop detection via back-edge identification on the dominance tree.
    2. Per-loop induction variable analysis: every vectorizable loop must have
       a primary integer induction variable with a compile-time-constant stride.
    3. Memory access collection and stride classification (unit-stride consecutive
       lanes are the prerequisite for plain vector loads/stores; non-unit strides
       degrade to gather/scatter).
    4. Data dependency analysis: detect RAW/WAR/WAW hazards and reject loops with
       loop-carried RAW dependencies that cannot be sunk into the same SIMD lane.
    5. Cost model: estimate scalar vs. vector cycle counts and reject loops whose
       projected speedup is below the profitability threshold (default 1.2x).
    6. Transformation: emit vector prologue, widen body instructions to vector
       opcodes, and emit scalar epilogue for the modulo-VF remainder.

    LOOP-VECTORIZATION vs. SLP:
    This pass implements loop-level vectorization (widening iteration semantics).
    Straight-line SLP (Superword-Level Parallelism) vectorization of basic blocks
    is performed by a complementary MIR pass and is intentionally out of scope
    here; the loop vectorizer only widens code that is already in a natural-loop
    nest with an analyzable induction variable.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The driver iterates the loop list produced by detect_natural_loops in the
    order returned by CFG traversal. Each loop is treated as an independent
    candidate; rejection of one loop never aborts the pass. Rejection paths
    increment context.rejected_loops and continue, while the success path falls
    through to transform_loop_to_vector and increments context.vectorized_loops.

    Continue-statements inside the analysis loop are used so that early-out
    rejection at any phase (no induction, loop-carried hazard, unprofitable)
    short-circuits the remaining analyses for that loop without affecting the
    state of the shared VectorizationContext (memory_accesses, dependencies,
    and cost_models dictionaries are keyed by loop_header_id so partial
    population is safe).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Pass cost is dominated by analyze_loop_dependencies, which is O(N^2) in the
    number of memory accesses per loop. Innermost-loop-only filtering keeps N
    small in practice (typical N=2 to 8). Detect_natural_loops itself is
    O(blocks * avg_successors) dominated by the dominance probe.
    @End Performance_Hints

    Display "========== Starting Loop Vectorization Pass =========="

    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Display "optimize_function_with_vectorization: null CFG"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create context
    Let context_ptr be proc create_vectorization_context with cfg_ptr
    If context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Display "optimize_function_with_vectorization: failed to create context"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 1: Detect natural loops
    Display "Step 1: Detecting natural loops"
    Let loops_found be proc detect_natural_loops with context_ptr

    If loops_found is equal to 0:
        Display "optimize_function_with_vectorization: no loops found"
        proc destroy_vectorization_context with context_ptr
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 2: Analyze each loop for vectorization
    Display "Step 2: Analyzing loops for vectorization"
    Let loop_candidates_dict be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 64
    Let loops_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 24
    Let loop_count be proc length from List with loops_list
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than loop_count:
        Let loop_info be proc get from List with loops_list, i

        Display "Analyzing loop "
        Display i

        Note: Analyze induction variables
        Let has_induction be proc analyze_induction_variables with context_ptr, loop_info

        If has_induction is equal to 0:
            Display "  No induction variable found, rejecting"
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 56, 0 Note: Not vectorizable
            Let rejected_loops be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 40
            Set rejected_loops to rejected_loops plus 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 40, rejected_loops
            Set i to i plus 1
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Collect memory accesses
        Let access_count be proc collect_memory_accesses with context_ptr, loop_info

        Note: Analyze dependencies
        Let dep_count be proc analyze_loop_dependencies with context_ptr, loop_info

        Note: Check for loop-carried dependencies
        Let is_safe be proc check_loop_carried_dependencies with context_ptr, loop_info

        If is_safe is equal to 0:
            Display "  Loop-carried dependencies found, rejecting"
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 56, 0
            Set rejected_loops to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 40
            Set rejected_loops to rejected_loops plus 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 40, rejected_loops
            Set i to i plus 1
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Compute cost model
        Let is_profitable be proc compute_vectorization_cost with context_ptr, loop_info

        If is_profitable is equal to 0:
            Display "  Vectorization not profitable, rejecting"
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 56, 0
            Set rejected_loops to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 40
            Set rejected_loops to rejected_loops plus 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 40, rejected_loops
            Set i to i plus 1
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Loop is vectorizable
        Display "  Loop is vectorizable!"
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with loop_info, 56, 1

        Note: Transform loop
        Let transformed be proc transform_loop_to_vector with context_ptr, loop_info

        If transformed is equal to 0:
            Display "  Transformation failed"
            Set rejected_loops to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 40
            Set rejected_loops to rejected_loops plus 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context_ptr, 40, rejected_loops
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Print statistics
    proc print_vectorization_stats with context_ptr

    Note: Cleanup
    proc destroy_vectorization_context with context_ptr

    Display "========== Loop Vectorization Pass Complete =========="

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "run_vectorization_pass" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Wrapper for vectorization pass execution.
    @End Reasoning

    Return proc optimize_function_with_vectorization with cfg_ptr
End Process

Process called "should_run_vectorization" that takes cfg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Cheap pre-pass filter that decides whether to run the full vectorizer.
    Vectorization is profitable only for functions containing at least one
    loop; for loop-free functions the analysis overhead is pure waste.

    The check is implemented as a single back-edge probe on the CFG, which
    is the same fundamental test that detect_natural_loops would perform.
    Running the cheap version first lets the pass manager skip the
    expensive dominance-tree construction for the common case of loop-free
    leaf functions.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegates to CFG.has_back_edges, which is O(B*S) at worst but
    short-circuits on the first back edge found. For typical loop-free
    functions this is O(B + E) total.
    @End Implementation

    If cfg_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if function has loops (back edges in CFG)
    Let has_loops be proc has_back_edges from CFG with cfg_ptr

    Return has_loops
End Process

Process called "get_vectorization_pass_name" that takes unit as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns pass name for debugging and reporting.
    @End Reasoning

    Return proc create_from_literal from String with "Loop Vectorization"
End Process

Process called "get_vectorization_pass_description" that takes unit as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns pass description.
    @End Reasoning

    Return proc create_from_literal from String with "Transforms scalar loops into vectorized SIMD code for performance"
End Process
